                         1992/1993 Pino Aliberti
                         1992/1993 Eric Krieger
                          All  rights  reserved



   This  document  describes, in short, but hopefully thorough, terms how
   to use the different functions in Point Manager V3.21.

   Please  read  it carefully !  Many of the problems an user can have in
   the use of a program, can be solved by carefully reading the manual.

   From  version V3.10,  I  take  the  place of Mario Pacchiarotti in the
   development of Point Manager.

   This  version  is  usable  also from unregistered users, if it doesn't
   find  the keyfile in MAIL:  it will simply open a small reminder that,
   for a few seconds, cannot be closed.  This doesn't means that you have
   not to register to PM.  Please read the @{"Registration" LINK Registration} chapter.

   This  version  fixes  some little bugs in v 3.20 (that was usable only
   from  registered users) and has also some little improvments.  But for
   all those who are still using v 3.10 it is a big improvement.

   The syntax of some configuration switches has changed from V3.10, I've
   described all this changes in the CFGchanges.TXT file.  Please read it
   carefully  before starting PM V3.21.  All the changes will be found in
   Changes.TXT.

   This  should  be  the  last  3.* version of PM.  Actually I'm going to
   start  the development of a completely  new version of PM.  I'll start
   its  coding  from scratch, implementing a completely new message base,
   and a new, fully configurable, graphical user interface.

@ENDNODE Introduction

@NODE Overall "Overall"
@PREV "Introduction"
@NEXT "Bounds"
@TOC "Main"
   Overall

   Point Manager is a Tosser, Scanner and Editor for any Amiga Point.

   Even though PM performs so many tasks, you will need a good Mailer (eg
   TrapDoor).   PM actually integrates all tasks you can perform with any
   Tosser/Scanner  and  Editor,  and beyond that you will find some extra
   utilities that you won't find in any other program.

   When you are new to FidoNet (or compatible NetWorks) or Point concept,
   please  find  and  read a file called FidoNet.Man first (from the same
   people  as TrapDoor, TrapList, etc.), which covers all information you
   need.

   This  version  of  PM only needs 1 (ONE) configuration file which sets
   all  the  parameters  necessary  for  PM to work.  Do not despair, the
   majority   of   the   options   in  the  configuration  file  are  for
   customization purposes only, so you don't have to deal with those from
   the  first-time configuration, you can use the defaults, which assures
   you that PM will run error-free.

   As  some  of the parameters have been changed or have been removed, it
   is advised that you read the entire manual before using the new PM !!!

@ENDNODE Overall

@NODE Bounds "Bonds"
@PREV "Overall"
@NEXT "Installation"
@TOC "Main"
   Bounds

   PM requires some bonds to work properly:

  - PM  needs  a stack of at least 12000 bytes.  Set  it  manually before
    starting PM with: 'Stack 12000', or better, insert that line in  your
    S:Shell-Startup.

  - 'Run' command must be present in the system path (C:) (or Resident with AmigaDos 2.0+)

  - diskfont.library MUST be present in LIBS:

  - reqtools.library MUST be present in LIBS:

  - The supplied fonts PMBrowse and PMFont MUST be in FONTS:

  - In  order  to  call Config PM (Edit CFG) from the @{"Project Menu" LINK PD_Menu_AreasWindow} of PM,
    CPM must be present in the system path (before running PM).

@ENDNODE Bounds

@NODE Installation "Installation of PM V3.21"
@PREV "Bounds"
@NEXT "Configuration"
@TOC "Main"
   Installation

   To install PM you have to do the following:

   - Copy  PM321/Bin/PM and  PM321/Bin/CPM in your C: directory or in any
     directory in the system path.

   - Copy  the supplied fonts  (all files and directories in PM321/Fonts)
     in  your  FONTS:  directory.  The old PMFont and PMBrowse fonts, are
     no longer sufficient.  Please use the NEW ones !

   - Copy  PM321/libs13/ReqTools.library  (if you are running WB 1.2/1.3)
     or  PM321/Libs20/ReqTools.library   (if  you  are running WB 2.x) to
     your LIBS:  directory.


   To  improve  the use of a 'standard' setup/configuration, please use a
   directory  structure  like  this  (which  is  also  used  by the Trap*
   programs!):


     MAIL:   --+- Bin                        (executables)
     (config   |- Docs                       (manuals, documentation)
      files)   |- Scripts                    (shell scripts)
               |- Rexx                       (arexx scripts)
               |- Inbound                    (inbound mail and files)
               |- Outbound                   (outbound mail and files)
               |- Nodelist                   (nodelist, userlist, etc.)
               |- Matrix -+- Netmail.FIDO \
               |          |- Matrix.AMY    > (netmail)
               |          |- [...]        /
               |
               |- Echo -+- AMIGA          \
               |        |- PM              > (echomail areas)
               |        |- [...]          /
               |
               |- Stats                      (statistic files)


@ENDNODE Installation

@NODE Configuration "Configuration of PM V3.21"
@PREV "Installation"
@NEXT "Operation"
@TOC "Main"
   Configuration

   As  mentioned before, PM needs only one configuration file in order to
   work  (also  for  more  than  one Boss, Net or Point-Addresses!).  The
   format  of  the  file  is plain text, so you can edit it with a normal
   Text Editor.

   However  it  is better to use CPM for editing your configuration file,
   as it prevents any kind of syntax error and makes the configuration of
   PM easier.

   By  default, CPM looks for a file called PManager.CFG placed in MAIL:.
   If  it  is somewhere else, or it is named in a different way, you have
   to  specify  its name after CPM, e.g.  'CPM df0:ConfigFile' or you can
   load it from within CPM from a Pull-Down menu with a FileRequester.

   If  you  manually  edit  the configuration file, remember that you can
   only  insert a single parameter per line (starting with an hash-symbol
   "#"), and that the lines must end with a Line Feed!!

   Some parameters will not work correctly if you haven't already defined
   other  parameters, so, if you do manually edit the configuration file,
   please  follow  the  order found in the supplied example configuration
   file or in any file created by CPM.

   The  following  paragraphs  will  describe  all  the parameters in the
   configuration  file,  in the same order they are placed in the windows
   of  CPM.   The name of the paragraph is the same as the gadget in CPM.
   In  square  brakets  you  can  find  the  syntax  of the corresponding
   parameter of the configuration file.

   Lets start CPM with:

   CPM <configfile>

   @{"CPM" LINK CPMMain} will open its Main Window.  You will find there are eight gadgets,
   you  should  guess  what 'Quit' and 'Save' are designed for; the other
   six  gadgets  (System,  Misc,  Areas,  Layout, Text, Custom) will open
   their own configuration windows.

   From  this  version, there is also a 'Project' menu with four entries:
   'Open...', 'Save', 'Save as...' and 'Quit'.

@ENDNODE Configuration 

@NODE CPMMain "Configuration: CPM Main Window"
@PREV "Configuration"
@NEXT "System_Window"
@TOC "Configuration"
   Configuration with CPM

   When  CPM  is  started  succesfully,  the  Main Window of CPM contains
   several gadgets:


           Config PM - Main Window -

           @{" SYSTEM " LINK System_Window} @{" MISC   " LINK Misc_Window} @{" AREAS  " LINK Areas_Window}
           @{" LAYOUT " LINK Cfg_Layout_Window} @{" TEXT   " LINK TextW} @{" CUSTOM " LINK Custom_Cfg_Window}
           @{"  Save  " LINK SaveW} @{"  (C)   " LINK Introduction} @{"  Quit  " LINK QuitW}


   Each gadget, and its function, will be discussed when selecting one.

@ENDNODE CPMMain

@NODE System_Window "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window"
@PREV "CPMMain"
@NEXT "Misc_Window"
@TOC "CPMMain"
   System Configuration Window

   @{" Sysop Name     " LINK Sysop}   @{" Serial         " LINK Serial_Number}   @{" Inbound        " LINK Inbound}
                      @{" MsgOrder       " LINK MsgOrder}   @{" Outbound       " LINK Outbound}
   @{" Addresses      " LINK Addresses}   @{" EchoLevel      " LINK EchoLevel}   @{" WorkDir        " LINK WorkDir}
                      @{" LogLevel       " LINK LogLevel}   @{" Stats Dir      " LINK StatDir}
                      @{" DeleteChar     " LINK DeleteChar}   @{" Nodelist       " LINK NodeList}
                      @{" MaxMsgLth      " LINK Message_Length}   @{" Userlist       " LINK UserList}
                                         @{" Editor         " LINK Editor}
                                         @{" Mailer         " LINK Mailer}
                                         @{" DeCruncher     " LINK DeCruncher}
   @{" Default Origin " LINK Def_Origin}                      @{" LogFile        " LINK LogFile}

@ENDNODE System_Window

@NODE Sysop "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => Sysop"
@PREV "System_Window"
@NEXT "Addresses"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#SYSOP "Name Surname"]

   With  this parameter you tell  PM what your Name and Surname is.  This
   will be  used to identify messages  addressed to you, and to insert in
   the outgoing messages as a default.


   Example:

   #SYSOP "Pino Aliberti"

@ENDNODE Sysop

@NODE Addresses "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => Addresses"
@PREV "Sysop"
@NEXT "Def_Origin"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#ADDRESS @{"PointAddr" LINK PointAddress} @{"(switch,switch,..)" LINK Switch} @{"BossAddr" LINK BossAddress} @{"FakeNet" LINK FakeNet} @{"Cruncher" LINK Cruncher}]

   This gadget lists all the addresses of the point.

   You can Add, Edit or Delete an Address.

   If  you click on the 'Add or 'Edit' gadget, CPM will open a @{"new window" LINK Address_Cfg_Window}
   where  you  can  insert  all the  required data.   In order to edit an
   existing  address,  you have to click on the 'Edit' gadget and then on
   the  address  you want to edit.  The 'Delete' gadget works in the same
   way as the 'Edit' gadget.

   You can Edit up to 30 different addresses.

   ..Beware.. The addresses (Point and Boss) must be 5 Dimensional!!

   Thus, zone:region/net.point@domain



   Examples:

   #ADDRESS 2:335/602.2@fidonet (BUNDLE4D,PACK4D,FLO4D,NODOMAIN,SEEN2D,\
            PATH2D) 2:335/602.0@fidonet 0 "C:LhA a"

   This example could be used when running Fidonet (especially the SEEN2D
   and PATH2D switches!).


   #ADDRESS 39:102/1.2@fidonet (BUNDLE4D,PACK4D,FLO4D,DOMAIN,SEEN4D,\
            PATH4D) 39:102/1.0@amiganet 0 "C:LhA a"

   This example could be used when running AmigaNet.


   Note: #ADDRESS should be 1 line, without spaces between the switches!!

         The  "\"  in  the  examples  above, are only used to 'break' the
         lines  in  this  example  (be sure that they don't exist in your
         config file!)

         
@ENDNODE Addresses

@NODE Address_Cfg_Window "CPM: SYSTEM/ADDRESS Configuration Window"
@PREV "Addresses"
@NEXT "Def_Origin"
@TOC "Addresses"

   The  Address  Configuration  Window  of CPM does contain the following
   Gadgets and Switches, all part of the #ADDRESS config-line:


   @{" Point Address " LINK PointAddress}                     @{" Switches      " LINK Switch}
   @{" Boss Address  " LINK BossAddress}
   @{" Cruncher      " LINK Cruncher}   @{" FakeNet       " LINK FakeNet}

@ENDNODE Address_Cfg_Window

@NODE PointAddress "CPM: SYSTEM/ADDRESS Configuration Window => Point Address"
@PREV "Address_Cfg_Window"
@NEXT "BossAddress"
@TOC "Address_Cfg_Window"
   Point Address

   This is the 5 dimensional address of your point in the format:
   Zone:Net/Node/Point@Domain   e.g.  2:335/602.2@fidonet

@ENDNODE PointAddress

@NODE BossAddress "CPM: SYSTEM/ADDRESS Configuration Window => Boss Address"
@PREV "PointAddress
@NEXT "Cruncher"
@TOC "Address_Cfg_Window"
   Boss Address

   This is the 5 dimensional address of your Boss in the format:
   Zone:Net/Node/Point@Domain   e.g.  2:335/602.0@fidonet

@ENDNODE BossAddress

@NODE Cruncher "CPM: SYSTEM/ADDRESS Configuration Window => Cruncher"
@PREV "BossAddress
@NEXT "FakeNet"
@TOC "Address_Cfg_Window"
   Cruncher

   Indicates  what  command will be used to compress the packages created
   by  the  Point.  The program (method) you decide to use must be agreed
   with your BOSS.  e.g.  C:LhA a

@ENDNODE Cruncher

@NODE FakeNet "CPM: SYSTEM/ADDRESS Configuration Window => FakeNet"
@PREV "Cruncher"
@NEXT "Switch"
@TOC "Address_Cfg_Window"
   FakeNet

   Some  (old)  mailers can still not handle 4 or 5 Dimensional addresses
   properly,  and  thus  limited  to  2  Dimensional  addresses.  You can
   imagine that running 2D or 3D, there is no way to represent your point
   address.  That's where a Fakenet comes in (also called PointNet).

   When  the  fakenet  is  used, PM makes 2D packets.  You must provide a
   value  for this, or use 0 if you are using 4D addressing.  Insert here
   ONLY your Fake_NET_, not your complete FakeAddress.  e.g 25602 and NOT
   25602/2 !

@ENDNODE FakeNet

@NODE Switch "CPM: SYSTEM/ADDRESS Configuration Window => Switches"
@PREV "FakeNet"
@NEXT "Def_Origin"
@TOC "Address_Cfg_Window"
   Switches

   Domain (DOMAIN or NODOMAIN)
     specifies if PM will insert the Domain in your address
     Y - Insert the Domain (DOMAIN)           e.g. (2:335/602.2@fidonet)
     N - Do not insert the Domain (NODOMAIN)  e.g. (2:335/602.2)

   Bundle (BUNDLE2D or BUNDLE4D)
     specifies how PM will name its bundles:
     2D - Use 2 dimensional names  e.g. 231a43ba.FR0
     4D - Use 4 dimensional names  e.g. 2.335.602.0.FR0

   .PKT (PACK2D, PACK4D)
     specifies the type of PKT created by PM:
     2D - make 2D packet (fakenet/point). Use it if your boss  works with
          a stoneage tosser/scanner.
          Be sure that you use a @{"fakenet" LINK FakeNet} not equal to 0!
     4D - make 4D packet following FSC-0039
          Fakenet  should  be  set  to  0 (but it won't be used if set to
          another value).

   .FLO (FLO2D or FLO4D)
     specifies how PM will name its .FLO files:
     2D - Use 2 dimensional names  e.g. 231a43ba.FLO
     4D - Use 4 dimensional names  e.g. 2.335.602.0.FLO

   Seen-By (SEEN2D or SEEN4D)
     specifies the type of Seen-By lines used by PM:
     2D - Use 2 dimensional Seen-By  e.g. SEEN-BY: 335/601 602
     4D - Use 4 dimensional Seen-By  e.g. SEEN-BY: 2:335/601 602 .1 .2

   Path (PATH2D or PATH4D)
     specifies the type of Path lines used by PM:
     2D - Use 2 dimensional Path  e.g. PATH: 335/601 602
     4D - Use 4 dimensional Path  e.g. PATH: 2:335/602.2 601 602



   When  you  want  to use PM for Fidonet, you must use SEEN2D and PATH2D
   (part  of  the rules).  When running within AmigaNet (for example), it
   is  possible  to  use SEEN4D and PATH4D, but this depends on your Boss
   (when in doubt, you should ask him what to use!).

   The  BUNDLE,  PACK  and  FLO  switches  must  be set according to your
   Mailer.  When using TrapDoor (V1.80+) you can set them all to 4D!

@ENDNODE Switch

@NODE Def_Origin "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => Default Origin"
@PREV "Addresses"
@NEXT "Serial_Number"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#ORIGIN "Origin"]

   Defines  your  default Origin line.  PM uses this Origin when you have
   created  a  message for an area that doesn't have an individual Origin
   line specified (@{"#AREAORIGIN" LINK AreaOrigin}).

   The  maximum length of the Origin line is 78 characters, including the
   string " * Origin:" and your address, like "(2:335/602.2@fidonet)".

   When  you  enter  "  This  is  just a test with Point Manager " in the
   string-gadget, your real Origin line would be:

   * Origin: This is just a test with Point Manager (2:335/602.2@fidonet)


   Example:

   #ORIGIN " Final Version of Point Manager V3.21 "

@ENDNODE Def_Origin

@NODE Serial_Number "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => Serial"
@PREV "Def_Origin"
@NEXT "MsgOrder"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#SERIAL xxxx]

   @{"Registered  users" LINK Registration}  should  write  their registration number here.  You
   must also have the PM Keyfile in MAIL:.


   Example:

   #SERIAL 0001

@ENDNODE Serial_Number

@NODE MsgOrder "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => MsgOrder"
@PREV "Serial_Number"
@NEXT "EchoLevel"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#MSGORDER parameter(s)]

   This  parameter  specifies  the default order that PM will use to list
   messages.

   The possible parameters are:

   F    Sort by [FROM]
   T    Sort by [TO]
   S    Sort by [SUBJECT]
   D    Sort by [DATE]
   N    Sort by [MESSAGE-NUMBER]

   It  is  possible to use more than one parameter simultaneously, if you
   for  example,  use  #MSGORDER  SD,  PM will first sort the messages by
   [SUBJECT] and then by [DATE].


   Example:

   #MSGORDER N

@ENDNODE MsgOrder

@NODE EchoLevel "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => EchoLevel"
@PREV "MsgOrder"
@NEXT "LogLevel"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#ECHOLEVEL n]

   This parameter defines Point Manager's verbosity during writing to the
   Standard Output.

   A  level of 0 produces no information to be written, a level of 5 sets
   maximum verbosity.  A good choice could be '3'.


   Example:

   #ECHOLEVEL 4

@ENDNODE EchoLevel

@NODE LogLevel "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => LogLevel"
@PREV "EchoLevel"
@NEXT "DeleteChar"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#LOGLEVEL n]

   This parameter defines Point Manager's verbosity during writing to the
   log file (@{"#LOGFILE" LINK LogFile}).

   A  level  of 0 produces no information to be stored in the log file, a
   level of 5 sets maximum verbosity.


   Example:

   #LOGLEVEL 4

@ENDNODE LogLevel

@NODE DeleteChar "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => DeleteChar"
@PREV "LogLevel"
@NEXT "Message_Length"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#DELETECHAR character]

   Specifies  what  character  to  use, in order to tell TrapDoor (or any
   other   Mailer)  what  type  of  operation  it  should  perform  after
   transmission.


   The characters available for use with TrapDoor are :

   # Transmit the file without cancelling it
   ^ Cancel the file and report this in the LogFile
   - Cancel the file and do not report this in the LogFile


   Example:

   #DELETECHAR ^

@ENDNODE DeleteChar

@NODE Message_Length "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => MaxMsgLth"
@PREV "DeleteChar"
@NEXT "Inbound"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#MAXMSGLTH n]

   Point  Manager  uses  a  static  buffer  to  work with messages.  This
   parameter defines the buffer size.  A good choice is something between
   24000 and 32000.

   You cannot work with messages longer than MaxMsgLth !!!


   Example:

   #MAXMSGLTH 32000

@ENDNODE Message_Length

@NODE Inbound "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => Inbound"
@PREV "Message_Length"
@NEXT "Outbound"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#INBOUND directory]

   This  defines  where  PM  should look for INCOMING mail from your BOSS
   during  @{"IMPORT" LINK PMImport}.   It is very important that this directory is the same
   as that specified in your Mailer.

   When defining the directory, be sure to end it with either a "/" or an
   ":".


   Example:

   #INBOUND MAIL:Inbound/

@ENDNODE Inbound

@NODE Outbound "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => Outbound"
@PREV "Inbound"
@NEXT "WorkDir"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#OUTBOUND directory]

   This  parameter  specifies  where PM will store packets during @{"EXPORT" LINK PMExport}.
   As  with  the  Inbound directory, this directory should be the same as
   that specified in your Mailer.

   When defining the directory, be sure to end it with either a "/" or an
   ":".


   Example:

   #OUTBOUND MAIL:Outbound/

@ENDNODE Outbound

@NODE WorkDir "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => WorkDir"
@PREV "Outbound"
@NEXT "StatDir"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#WORKDIR directory]

   Defines  in which directory PM should place its temporary files.  Best
   place  is  RAM:  or VD0:, because this will work the quickest, but you
   should have enough Memory!

   When  you'll receive big mail-packets and PM wants to process (IMPORT)
   them,  when  you don't have enough memory left, PM tries to inform you
   about  it, and will stop the processing of it.  But it's possible that
   there's  no  Memory  left to stop the actions, and to inform you about
   it.  In this case you could loose messages!

   Therefore  it's good to make copies of your incoming mail-packets in a
   temporary directory, so you can always import them again.


   When defining the directory, be sure to end it with either a "/" or an
   ":".


   Example:

   #WORKDIR T:

@ENDNODE WorkDir

@NODE StatDir "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => Stats Dir"
@PREV "WorkDir"
@NEXT "NodeList"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#STATS directory]

   Defines  the  path and filename in which directory PM should place its
   statistic file.

   From this version PM uses a single file for all the statistics.


   Example:

   #STATS MAIL:PMStats/PM.STATS

@ENDNODE StatDir

@NODE NodeList "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => Nodelist"
@PREV "StatDir"
@NEXT "UserList"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#(NO)NODELIST "nodelist"]

   There is a little nodelist support in PM 3.21.  You must use a simple,
   not compiled, nodelist file.  PM will use it to search for the name of
   sysop in addressing.  You can also use a wildcard, e.g.  'MAIL:Node#?'

   You can disable the Nodelist search by leaving this gadget empty, or
   to put #NONODELIST in the config.


   The Nodelist should be in a not compiled format, like:

   Host,102,AmigaNET_Sud,Italy,Maurizio_Fabiani,39-862-26313,9600,CM,XR,\
       V32B,H14,V42B
   ,1,MAUI_for_Amiga,L'Aquila_Italy,Maurizio_Fabiani,39-862-26313,9600,\
       CM,XR,V32B,H14,V42B
   ,2,MAUI_for_Amiga_II,L'Aquila_Italy,Maurizio_Fabiani,39-862-419891,\
       9600,CM,XR,V32B,V42B
   ,3,MANGAZONE_BBS,Roma_Italy,Ivan_Pintori,39-6-7029438,9600,XR,V42B,HST
   ...etc...


   Note: The  "\"  in  the  examples  above, are only used to 'break' the
         lines  in  this  example  (be sure that they don't exist in your
         Nodelist file!)


   When  you  want  to  write a Netmail (Matrix) message to Ivan Pintori,
   just enter

   Ivan_Pintori

   in  the To:  field (without inverted commas!) of the @{"Parameters Window" LINK Editor_Parameters}
   for Netmail, and PM will search trough the Nodelist for this name (and
   in this example it will find 39:102/3).


   Example:

   #NODELIST "MAIL:Nodelist/AmyList.#?"

   or:

   #NONODELIST

@ENDNODE NodeList

@NODE UserList "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => Userlist"
@PREV "NodeList"
@NEXT "Editor"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#(NO)USERLIST "filename"]

   This  is  the name of the Userlist file.  PM will use it to search for
   the name of sysop in addressing, when writing a message.

   A line in the Userlist MUST be in the format:

   Surname, Name Address Nickname

   e.g.:

   Aliberti, Pino 2:335/602.2   PinoA
   , AreaFix      2:335/602.0   af
   , RoadRunner   9:999/999.999


   Note: AreaFix is one name. Use it with the ", ". This is also true for
         other 'persons' with one name!!

   And the address MUST be a 4D address (Fx: 2:335/602.0).


   When  you  want  to  write a Netmail (Matrix) message to, for example,
   Pino Aliberti, just enter:

   PinoA

   (which is the NickName) in the To:  field of the @{"Parameters Window" LINK Editor_Parameters} for
   Netmail,  and PM will search trough the Userlist for this name (and in
   this example it will find and use 2:335/602.2).


   You can use also wildcard, e.g. 'MAIL:User#?' for the Userlist!!

   And you can disable the Nodelist search by leaving this gadget empty,
   or by using #NOUSERLIST in the config file.


   Example:

   #USERLIST "MAIL:Nodelist/UserList"

@ENDNODE UserList

@NODE Editor "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => Editor"
@PREV "UserList"
@NEXT "Mailer"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#EDITOR "program %s"]

   Tells  PM  what  command  to  use,  in  order  to start your favourite
   Text-Editor,  when writing or editing a message.  PM will replace '%s'
   with the name of the temporary file to edit.

   PM  does  not have an internal Text-Editor, therefore you must specify
   and  use  an  external Text-Editor.  If possible you should use a non-
   detaching  Editor  (or in case of using the great Cygnus-Editor, use a
   Commandline-switch  called  "-keepio"  or  "-sticky",  to make it non-
   detachable).


   Example:

   #EDITOR "C:Ed %s -sticky"

@ENDNODE Editor

@NODE Mailer "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => Mailer"
@PREV "Editor"
@NEXT "DeCruncher"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#POLL "command"]

   This  is  the command that PM will execute when the @{"Poll gadget" LINK PM_Area_Gadgets} in the
   Areas  Window of PM is selected.  Remember to specify the full path of
   the command.  e.g.  'C:TrapDoor Call Boss'.


   Example:

   #POLL "MAIL:Bin/TrapDoor Call Boss"

@ENDNODE Mailer

@NODE DeCruncher "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => DeCruncher"
@PREV "Mailer"
@NEXT "LogFile"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#DECRUNCHER "command"]

   Indicates what command will be used to decompress packages arriving at
   your  Point.   The  program you decide to use must be agreed with your
   BOSS.   e.g.   'C:LHARC  X' .  Of course you can also use an universal
   decruncher, like UX.rexx or XArc.rexx.


   Example:

   #DECRUNCHER "C:LhA x"

   or 

   #DECRUNCHER "MAIL:Rexx/UX.rexx"

   when  you  want  to  support 'all' de-archive-methods with the UX.rexx
   script.

@ENDNODE DeCruncher

@NODE LogFile "CPM: SYSTEM Configuration Window => LogFile"
@PREV "DeCruncher"
@NEXT "System_Window"
@TOC "System_Window"

   [#LOGFILE "filename"]

   Is the name of the Log File written by PM.

   The amount of information is determined with @{"#LOGLEVEL" LINK LogLevel}.


   Example:

   #LOGFILE "MAIL:PManager.Log"

@ENDNODE LogFile

@NODE Misc_Window "CPM: MISC Configuration Window"
@PREV "System_Window"
@NEXT "Areas_Window"
@TOC "CPMMain"
   Miscellaneus Configuration Window

   @{" CreateDir     " LINK CreateDir}   @{" QuickExport   " LINK Quick_Export}   @{" Beep   " LINK Beep}   @{" CheckDupe   " LINK CheckDupe}
   @{" CrunchMatrix  " LINK CrunchMatrix}   @{" Quiet         " LINK Quiet}
   @{" ExitDMouse    " LINK ExitDM}   @{" Reflow        " LINK Reflow}
   @{" ForceOrigin   " LINK ForceOrigin}   @{" ShortLink     " LINK Short_Link}
   @{" FormFeed      " LINK FormFeed}   @{" TurboScan     " LINK TurboScan}   @{" ArchiveMethod " LINK Archive_Method}
   @{" HideKludge    " LINK HideKludge}   @{" UnixMatch     " LINK UnixMatch}
   @{" HoldMem       " LINK HoldMem}
   @{" Index         " LINK PMIndex}
   @{" KeepMatrix    " LINK KeepMatrix}                     @{" ArchiveFile   " LINK Archive_File}
   @{" KeepSysop     " LINK KeepSysop}

@ENDNODE Misc_Window

@NODE CreateDir "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => CreateDir"
@PREV "Misc_Window"
@NEXT "CrunchMatrix"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)CREATEDIR]

   If  CreateDir is activated, PM will automagically create the directory
   associated with every area, if it doesn't already exist.


   Note:  PM can only create a non-existing directory 1 level down.

@ENDNODE CreateDir

@NODE CrunchMatrix "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => CrunchMatrix"
@PREV "CreateDir"
@NEXT "ExitDM"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)CRUNCHMATRIX]

   If  CrunchMatrix  is  activated  PM  will  compress  Netmail  Packets.
   Otherwise  they  will  be left uncompressed (set #CRUNCHMATRIX only if
   you do not send Crash Matrix Mail!).

@ENDNODE CrunchMatrix

@NODE ExitDM "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => ExitDMouse"
@PREV "CrunchMatrix"
@NEXT "ForceOrigin"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)EXITDMOUSE]

   If  you  select  ExitDMouse,  you  can close PM windows with the Right
   Mouse-Button.


   Note:  however, you can't quit the Areas (first) Window with the Right
          Mouse-Button.

@ENDNODE ExitDM

@NODE ForceOrigin "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => ForceOrigin"
@PREV "ExitDM"
@NEXT "FormFeed"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)FORCEORIGIN]

   This  option  inserts your Point Manager Origin in your message during
   @{"EXPORT" LINK PMImport}  phase.   This  option is only useful if you don't use PM as an
   editor.

@ENDNODE ForceOrigin

@NODE FormFeed "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => FormFeed"
@PREV "ForceOrigin"
@NEXT "HideKludge"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)FORMFEED]

   If  you specify FormFeed, a formfeed will be sent to the printer after
   every   message  that  PM  prints.    For  more  information  see  the
   @{"-P command" LINK PM_Batch_CmdP}.

@ENDNODE FormFeed

@NODE HideKludge "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => HideKludge"
@PREV "FormFeed"
@NEXT "HoldMem"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#HIDEKLUDGE/ #SHOWKLUDGE]

   Determines  whether  or not the Kludge lines are shown, while Browsing
   (reading) messages.

   Kludges are,  for example, the MSGID:, PID:, PATH: and SEEN-BY: lines.

@ENDNODE HideKludge

@NODE HoldMem "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => HoldMem"
@PREV "HideKludge"
@NEXT "PMIndex"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)HOLDMEM]

   When  PM opens an area, it will allocate a certain amount of memory in
   which it stores information about all messages in the area.

   If  you select HoldMem, this informations will be kept in memory until
   you  shut  down PM (or until you have no more memory left).  This will
   make  PM  faster  in  many  procedures.   All  the Index files will be
   updated at the end of the session.

   @{b}REMEMBER:@{ub}   @{b}NEVER@{ub}  shut  down  or  reset  your Amiga while PM is still
   running.  Some Index files would not be updated.  PM will rebuild them
   in  the next session, but this operation would takes some time, and it
   is  possible  that  you disk will be unvalidated (in this case, repair
   this first before running PM again!).

   If you do not select HoldMem, everytime you exit from an area, PM will
   update the Index and release all the Area Memory (which works slower).

@ENDNODE HoldMem

@NODE PMIndex "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => Index"
@PREV "HoldMem"
@NEXT "KeepMatrix"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)INDEX]

   When this option is selected, PM will store the message's header in an
   Index file.  This will make PM incredibly fast on some operations. Use
   this option whenever you can.  If you select Index you should deselect
   @{"TurboScan" LINK TurboScan}!!! (CPM will do this for you).

   With  Index,  PM  will be at least 4 times faster than with TurboScan.

   The Index files will be 170 bytes * msg long.

@ENDNODE PMIndex

@NODE KeepMatrix "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => KeepMatrix"
@PREV "PMIndex"
@NEXT "KeepSysop"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)KEEPMATRIX]

   When  you specify KeepMatrix, all the messages in the area(s) you have
   defined  as  MATRIX  will be left untouched by the @{"DELETE" LINK PMDel} command.

   If  you  want  to  delete  these  messages  you  have to enter in the
   @{"Messages" LINK PMMessW}  or  @{"Browse  window" LINK PM_Browse_Window},  select the messages and DELETE it from
   there.

@ENDNODE KeepMatrix

@NODE KeepSysop "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => KeepSysop"
@PREV "KeepMatrix"
@NEXT "Quick_Export"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)KEEPSYSOP]

   If  you  specify  KeepSysop, all messages addressed to you and written
   from you will be left untouched by the @{"DELETE" LINK PMDel} command.

   If  you  want  to  delete  these  messages  you  have to enter in the
   @{"Messages" LINK PMMessW}  or  @{"Browse  window" LINK PM_Browse_Window},  select the messages and DELETE it from
   there.

@ENDNODE KeepSysop

@NODE Quick_Export "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => QuickExport"
@PREV "KeepSysop"
@NEXT "Quiet"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)QUICKEXPORT]

   If  you  specify QuickExport, PM will try to Export messages only from
   the  areas  where it 'knows' you have written a message (when you have
   selected other Areas too).

@ENDNODE Quick_Export

@NODE Quiet "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => Quiet"
@PREV "Quick_Export"
@NEXT "Reflow"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)QUIET]

   If you select Quiet, PM won't notify you when it encounters a problem.

@ENDNODE Quiet

@NODE Reflow "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => Reflow"
@PREV "Quiet"
@NEXT "Short_Link"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)REFLOW]

   If  you  select Reflow, when you write a message it will be "reflown"
   by PM.

   It will reflow only lines longer than 65 chr, that do not start with a
   space.   If  the first chr of the following line is a space or a LF/CR
   the line won't be reflown.

   In  any  case,  when  you save a message, you can always decide if it
   will be reflown or not, in the @{"Parameters Window" LINK Editor_Parameters}.

@ENDNODE Reflow

@NODE Short_Link "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => ShortLink"
@PREV "Reflow"
@NEXT "TurboScan"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#SHORTLINK/#LONGLINK]

   With  ShortLink enabled, PM will display in the Browse Window a simple
   flag to bring out the presence of linked messages.

   With  ShorthLink  disabled PM will display some more information about
   the linked messages.

@ENDNODE Short_Link

@NODE TurboScan "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => TurboScan"
@PREV "Short_Link
@NEXT "UnixMatch"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)TURBOSCAN]

   Use  this  only  if  you  can't use @{"Index" PMIndex} (e.g.  if you haven't enough
   space on the disk).

   If  you  want  to use all the speed increase of TurboScan you must be
   sure  that  all  messages  are "Turbolized".  So everytime you change
   from Index to TurboScan you should issue the @{"PM -UT command" LINK PM_Batch_CmdU}.


   If you want to use Turboscan, you have to deselect @{"Index" LINK PMIndex}!!!  (CPM will
   do this for you).

@ENDNODE TurboScan

@NODE UnixMatch "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => UnixMatch"
@PREV "TurboScan"
@NEXT "Beep"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#UNIXMATCH/#AMIGAMATCH]

   Indicates how the pattern matching should be handled.

   If  you  select UnixMatch you can use "?" or "*", otherwise you should
   use "?" and "#"

@ENDNODE UnixMatch

@NODE Beep "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => Beep"
@PREV "UnixMatch"
@NEXT "Archive_Method"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)BEEP parameter]

   With this parameter you specify what type of beep you want to use:

   #BEEP SOUND: This produces a 'Beep'.
   #BEEP FLASH: This is the normal 'Flashing' screen.
   #BEEP BOTH : Select both, BEEP and FLASH
   #NOBEEP    : No action at all.

@ENDNODE Beep

@NODE Archive_Method "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => ArchiveMethod"
@PREV "Beep"
@NEXT "Archive_File"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#ARCHIVEMETHOD method]

   Indicates how archived files will be stored. You can choose between:

   FILE  : The archived files will be stored consecutively in a file.

   CRUNCH: The  archived  files  will  be  compressed  with  the  same
           compressor used as @{"Cruncher" LINK Cruncher} for the area.

@ENDNODE Archive_Method

@NODE Archive_File "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => ArchiveFile"
@PREV "Archive_Method"
@NEXT "CheckDupe"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#ARCHIVEFILE "filename"]

   Indicates  the name of the file where the messages you specify will be
   stored.

   Please  note  that in this version you can insert in the file name the
   following switches:

      %a - name of the area
      %p - path of the area
      %r - random number (0-100)
      %X - date and time in FidoNet format (12 Jan 90 23:23:12)
      %x - date in FidoNet format (12 Jan 91)

   e.g.   If  you  are  to  archive  a  message in the AMIGA area and you
          specify %a-Archive as filename, your message will be saved in a
          file called AMIGA-Archive


   Example:

   #ARCHIVEFILE "MAIL:Archives/%a%x"

@ENDNODE Archive_File

@NODE CheckDupe "CPM: MISC Configuration Window => CheckDupe"
@PREV "Archive_File"
@NEXT "Misc_Window"
@TOC "Misc_Window"

   [#(NO)CHECKDUPE parameter]

   This parameter tells PM how to handle dupes.

   If  you  select  CheckDupe  you  can tell to PM what to do if it finds
   dupes, while importing messages:

   KEEP: Tells you about the dupe, but imports it normally.
   BAD : Places the dupe in your BAD area.
   KILL: Does NOT IMPORT the dupe (the message will be killed/lost).

   If  you  have  not  selected CheckDupe, PM won't look for dupes.  This
   will  make  PM  faster  during  the  Import  phase so, if your PKT are
   normally  Dupes-Free  (i.e.   if  your Boss already checks his PKT for
   dupes), you can make PM not to check for dupes.


   Example:

   #CHECKDUPE BAD

@ENDNODE CheckDupe

@NODE Areas_Window "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window"
@PREV "Misc_Window"
@NEXT "Cfg_Layout_Window"
@TOC "CPMMain"
   Areas Configuration Window


   @{" Areas List " LINK Areas_List}   @{" Area Name        " LINK AreaName}   @{" Point Address    " LINK Area_PointAddress}
                  @{" Area Path        " LINK AreaPath}
                  @{" Area Logo        " LINK AreaLogo}   @{" Num. of Messages " LINK Number_Of_Msg}
                  @{" Area Origin      " LINK AreaOrigin}
                  @{" Area Prologue    " LINK AreaPrologue}   @{" Switches         " LINK Area_Switches}
                  @{" Area Font        " LINK AreaFont}

@ENDNODE Areas_Window

@NODE Areas_List "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Areas List"
@PREV "Areas_Window"
@NEXT "Cfg_Echo_Area"
@TOC "Areas_Window"
   Areas List

   This gadget lists all the areas of the point.

   You can Add, Delete or Move Up and Down an area in the list.

   When you click on 'Add' a new (empty) area will be added at the end of
   the list, and all the parameters of the previously selected area, will
   be  copied  in  the  gadgets (of course the Name and the Path won't be
   copied).

   When you select 'Del', the selected Area will be deleted.  A Requester
   will appear, with the question if you're sure to delete it!!

@ENDNODE Areas_List

@NODE Cfg_Echo_Area "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Area"
@PREV "Areas_List"
@NEXT "AreaName"
@TOC "Areas_Window"

   [#AREA @{"name" LINK AreaName} @{"path" LINK AreaPath} @{"address" LINK Area_PointAddress} @{"type" LINK Matrix_Echo_Bad} @{"abil" LINK WR} @{"sort" LINK Delete_By} @{"ndelete" LINK Number_Of_Msg} @{"range" LINK Int_Nat_Hub_Loc} @{"max" LINK Number_Of_Msg}]

   With this line you can define an Area.


   Examples:

   #AREA Matrix ECHO:Matrix.FIDO/ 2:335/602.2 MATRIX WRITE D 100 INT 300
   #AREA PM     ECHO:PM/          2:335/602.2 ECHO   WRITE N 100 INT 300
   #AREA BAD    ECHO:Bad/         2:335/602.2 BAD    READ  D 10  INT 100

@ENDNODE Cfg_Echo_Area

@NODE AreaName "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Area Name"
@PREV "Cfg_Echo_Area"
@NEXT "AreaPath"
@TOC "Areas_Window"
   Area Name

   This  is  the  Tag-Name  of the area.  Your BOSS (or its Areafix) will
   supply you with a list of all the available areas.

   You  CANNOT  use the same name for two different Areas.  Normally this
   won't happen with Echo areas that have different Tag-Names.

   But  you  also  have  to  name  also your Netmail Areas with different
   names, e.g.  MATRIX.FIDO or NETMAIL.AMY.


   Example:

   #AREA name path address type abil sort ndelete range max
         ^^^^
   #AREA AMIGA

   or

   #AREA MATRIX.FIDO

@ENDNODE AreaName

@NODE AreaPath "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Area Path"
@PREV "AreaName"
@NEXT "Number_Of_Msg"
@TOC "Areas_Window"
   Area Path

   This  is  the  path  of  the  directory  where  PM will store all the
   messages of the area, you must specify different directories for each
   area.

   When defining the directory, be sure to end it with either a "/" or an
   ":".  e.g.  'MAIL:MATRIX.FIDO/'


   Example:

   #AREA name path address type abil sort ndelete range max
              ^^^^
   #AREA      ECHO:AMIGA/

@ENDNODE AreaPath

@NODE Number_Of_Msg "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Num. of Messages"
@PREV "AreaPath"
@NEXT "Area_Switches"
@TOC "Areas_Window"
   Number of Messages

   MIN  This parameter specifies the minimum number of messages that will
        be left in the area after the @{"DELETE" LINK PMDel} command.

   MAX  This  parameter  specifies the maximum number of messages that PM
        will  handle  in  the  area.   All  the  exceding  msgs  will  be
        redirected to the @{"BAD" LINK Matrix_Echo_Bad} area.



   Example of MIN:

   #AREA name path address type abil sort ndelete range max
                                          ^^^^^^^
   #AREA                                  100


   Example of MAX:

   #AREA name path address type abil sort ndelete range max
                                                        ^^^
   #AREA                                                300

@ENDNODE Number_Of_Msg

@NODE Area_Switches "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Switches"
@PREV "Number_Of_Msg"
@NEXT "Area_PointAddress"
@TOC "Areas_Window"
   These  are  the  various  switches,  which  are  placed  in  the Areas
   Configuration Window.

   @{" Matrix-Echo-Bad  " LINK Matrix_Echo_Bad}   @{" Int-Nat-Hub-Loc  " LINK Int_Nat_Hub_Loc}
   @{" Delete By        " LINK Delete_By}   @{" Write-Read       " LINK WR}

@ENDNODE Area_Switches

@NODE Matrix_Echo_Bad "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Matrix-Echo-Bad"
@PREV "Area_Switches"
@NEXT "Int_Nat_Hub_Loc"
@TOC "Area_Switches"
   Switches Matrix, Echo and Bad

   These gadgets define the area type.

   Specify either:

    - MATRIX for your NetMail (Matrix) areas.

    - ECHO for your normal EchoMail areas.

    - BAD for your Bad area.


   You must have only one BAD area and at least one MATRIX area.


   Example:

   #AREA name path address type abil sort ndelete range max
                           ^^^^
   #AREA                   MATRIX

@ENDNODE Matrix_Echo_Bad

@NODE Int_Nat_Hub_Loc "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Int-Nat-Hub-Loc"
@PREV "Matrix_Echo_Bad"
@NEXT "Delete_By"
@TOC "Area_Switches"
   Switches Int, Nat, Hub and Loc

   This parameter specifies the range of the particular area.

   Specify either:

    - LOC (local).
    - NAT (national).
    - INT (international).
    - HUB (for 'statistical' functions. Functionally it is like NAT).

   If   you   specify   INT,  PM  will  use  the  International  Prologue
   (@{"#IPROLOGUE" LINK Def_IPrologue}) otherwise PM will use the normal Prologue (@{"#PROLOGUE" LINK Def_Prologue}),
   unless there is an @{"#AREAPROLOGUE" LINK AreaPrologue} for this Area.


   Example:

   #AREA name path address type abil sort ndelete range max
                                                  ^^^^^
   #AREA                                          NAT

@ENDNODE Int_Nat_Hub_Loc

@NODE Delete_By "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Delete By"
@PREV "Int_Nat_Hub_Loc"
@NEXT "WR"
@TOC "Area_Switches"
   Delete By

   Defines how PM will delete messages (when using the @{"DELETE" LINK PMDel} command).

   Specify either:

    - D(ATE)   PM  will  delete  messages  that  have  an  older  date of
               creation.

    - N(UMBER) PM  will delete messages that have an older date of import
               (a lower number).


   The same order will be used during @{"Renumber" LINK PMRenum}.


   Example:

   #AREA name path address type abil sort ndelete range max
                                     ^^^^
   #AREA                             N

@ENDNODE Delete_By

@NODE WR "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Write-Read"
@PREV "Delete_By"
@NEXT "Area_Switches"
@TOC "Area_Switches"
   Switches Write and Read

   Tells  PM whether or not you will be allowed to write a message in the
   area.

   Specify either:

    - WRITE you can Write messages.

    - READ you can only read messages.


   Example:

   #AREA name path address type abil sort ndelete range max
                                ^^^^
   #AREA                        WRITE

@ENDNODE WR

@NODE Area_PointAddress "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Area-Point Address"
@PREV "Area_Switches"
@NEXT "AreaLogo"
@TOC "Areas_Window"
   Area-Point Address

   Here  you  can  select the  Address  you  want to use in the area.  Of
   course,  you should  already have inserted all your addresses from the
   @{"System Window" LINK System_Window}.


   Example:

   #AREA name path address type abil sort ndelete range max
                   ^^^^^^^
   #AREA           2:335/602.2@fidonet
 

@ENDNODE Area_PointAddress

@NODE AreaLogo "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Area Logo"
@PREV "Area_PointAddress"
@NEXT "AreaOrigin"
@TOC "Areas_Window"

   [#AREALOGO areaname "logo"]

   This  parameter  lets  you define your logo or signature for the area,
   specified with "areaname".

   You  can  insert  several @{"control characters" LINK Phrase} in order to customize the
   logo.

   The total length of the text must be less than 245 chr.

   If you leave this gadget empty, PM will use the default @{"Logo" LINK Def_Logo}.


   Example:

   #AREALOGO PM "Ciao,\n Pino"
   #AREALOGO AMIGA "Best regards,\n\n Pino Aliberti"

@ENDNODE AreaLogo

@NODE AreaOrigin "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Area Origin"
@PREV "AreaLogo"
@NEXT "AreaPrologue"
@TOC "Areas_Window"

   [#AREAORIGIN areaname "origin"]

   This parameter lets you define the origin line for the area.

   The  maximum length of the Origin line is 78 characters, including the
   string " * Origin:" and your address, like "(2:335/602.2@fidonet)".

   If you leave this gadget empty, PM will use the default @{"Origin" LINK Def_Origin}.


   Example:

   #AREAORIGIN AMIGA " => AMIGA Goes International <= "

@ENDNODE AreaOrigin

@NODE AreaPrologue "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Area Prologue"
@PREV "AreaOrigin"
@NEXT "AreaFont"
@TOC "Areas_Window"

   [#AREAPROLOGUE areaname "prologue"]

   This parameter lets you define your prologue for the area.

   The  prologue  is  a phrase inserted in the head of your message, when
   you reply to a message.

   You  can  insert  several @{"control characters" LINK Phrase} in order to customize the
   prologue.

   The total length of the text must be less than 195 chr.

   If  you  leave  this gadget empty, PM will use the default @{"Prologue" LINK Def_Prologue} or
   @{"IPrologue" LINK Def_IPrologue} if you have defined the area as 'INT'.


   Example:

   #AREAPROLOGUE PM "Hi %f,\n\n In a message of <%D> you wrote:\n"

@ENDNODE AreaPrologue

@NODE AreaFont "CPM: AREAS Configuration Window => Area Font"
@PREV "AreaPrologue"
@NEXT "Areas_Window"
@TOC "Areas_Window"

   [#AREAFONT areaname fontname size]

   This parameter lets you define the font used by PM in the area.

   If you leave this gadget empty, PM will use the @{"default Font" LINK Font}.


   Examples:

   #AREAFONT AMIGA IBM.font 8
   #AREAFONT PM PMFont.font 8

@ENDNODE AreaFont

@NODE Cfg_Layout_Window "CPM: LAYOUT Configuration Window"
@PREV "Areas_Window"
@NEXT "TextW"
@TOC "CPMMain"
   Layout Configuration Window

   @{" Custom Screen " LINK Custom_Screen}   @{" Colors        " LINK Color}
   @{" Interlace     " LINK Interlace}
   @{" Browse Window " LINK Browse_Window}   @{" Font          " LINK Font}

@ENDNODE Cfg_Layout_Window

@NODE Custom_Screen "CPM: LAYOUT Configuration Window => Custom Screen"

   [#(NO)CUSTOMSCREEN width height]

   If  you  set  'Custom'  PM  will  open its windows on it's own screen,
   otherwise it will use your WorkBench screen.

   Under  WB 2.x (and higer) the custom screen will be opened as a Public
   Screen called "PMScreen".


   Example:

   #CUSTOMSCREEN 656 260    ;This  will open a CustomScreen with a format
                             of 656 x 260 pixels.
   or

   #NOCUSTOMSCREEN          ;This  will  open  a  normal  Window  on  the
                             Workbench screen.
   or

   #NOCUSTOMSCREEN xxx 220  ;This will open a Window with a format of xxx
                             (Width  of  the  Workbench  Screen)  by  220
                             pixels.

@ENDNODE Custom_Screen

@NODE Interlace "CPM: LAYOUT Configuration Window => Interlace"

   [#(NO)INTERLACE]

   If  you  set  'Interlace'  PM  will  open  its  windows with fonts and
   dimensions suited for an Interlaced screen.  If you have also selected
   'Custom' PM will open its Custom Screen in Interlaced mode.

@ENDNODE Interlace

@NODE Browse_Window "CPM: LAYOUT Configuration Window => Browse Window"
   Browse Window

   Using  Width and Height you can specify the size of your screen (when
   using   @{"#CUSTOMSCREEN" LINK Custom_Screen})  and  of  the  PM  Browse  Window  (also  with
   @{"#NOCUSTOMSCREEN" LINK Custom_Screen} selected).

@ENDNODE Browse_Window

@NODE Color "CPM: LAYOUT Configuration Window => Colors"

   [#(NO)COLORS xxx xxx xxx xxx]

   If  you  select Colors you can specify the colors you want to use with
   PM.  In  order  to  make  it  work  you  must specify the color as RGB
   Hexadecimal numbers.  e.g.  White would be 'FFF' , Red 'F00' and Black
   '000'.

   If  you click on the 'Palette' gadget you can choose the colors with a
   palette requester.

   When you do not select 'Colors', PM will use your WorkBench colors.

@ENDNODE Color

@NODE Font "CPM: LAYOUT Configuration Window => Font"

   [#FONT fontname.font size]

   Specifies  which  font PM will use on the Browse window.  You can also
   use proportional fonts.

   If  you  click  on  the 'Select' gadget you can choose the font with a
   Font requester.


   Example:

   #FONT PMBrowse.font 8

@ENDNODE Font

@NODE TextW "CPM: TEXT Configuration Window"
@PREV "Cfg_Layout_Window"
@NEXT "Custom_Cfg_Window"
@TOC "CPMMain"
   TEXT Configuration Window

   @{" Prologue   " LINK Def_Prologue}
   @{" IPrologue  " LINK Def_IPrologue}
   @{" ForwardTXT " LINK ForwTXT}
   @{" ReplyTXT   " LINK ReplyTXT}
   @{" Logo       " LINK Def_Logo}

@ENDNODE TextW

@NODE Def_Prologue "CPM: TEXT Configuration Window => Prologue"

   [#PROLOGUE "The phrase you choose as your prologue"]

   This phrase is inserted in the head of your message, when you reply to
   a message.  This is the default PROLOGUE that will be used if you have
   not supplied a @{"Prologue for the area" LINK AreaPrologue}.

   You  can  insert  several @{"control characters" LINK Phrase} in order to customize the
   prologue.

   The total length of the text must be less than 195 chr.

   When you press return, CPM will show you how your Prologue will "look"
   in your message.


   Example:

   #PROLOGUE PM "Hi %f,\n\n In a message of <%D> about <%S> you wrote:\n"

@ENDNODE Def_Prologue

@NODE Def_IPrologue "CPM: TEXT Configuration Window => IPrologue"

   [#IPROLOGUE "The phrase you choose as your IPrologue"]

   This phrase is inserted in the head of your message, when you reply to
   a  message.  This one is only inserted in areas marked as INT and only
   if you have not supplied a @{"Prologue for the area" LINK AreaPrologue}.

   You  can  insert  several @{"control characters" LINK Phrase} in order to customize the
   prologue.

   The total length of the text must be less than 195 chr.

   When  you  press  return,  CPM  will  show you how your IPrologue will
   "look" in your message.


   Example:

   #IPROLOGUE PM "Hi %f,\n\n In a message about <%S> you wrote:\n"

@ENDNODE Def_IPrologue

@NODE ForwTXT "CPM: TEXT Configuration Window => ForwardTXT"

   [#FORWARDTXT "text"]

   This  phrase is inserted in the head of your message, when you forward
   a message.

   You  can  insert  several @{"control characters" LINK Phrase} in order to customize the
   ForwardText.

   The total length of the text must be less than 500 chr.

   When  you  press  return,  CPM  will show you how your ForwardTXT will
   "look" in your message.


   Example:

   #FORWARDTXT "Message forwarded by %Y\n-------------------------------"

@ENDNODE ForwTXT

@NODE ReplyTXT "CPM: TEXT Configuration Window => ReplyTXT"

   [#REPLYTXT "Text"]

   This phrase is the text used by PM, when it automatically replies to a
   message in the AUTOREPLY utility (@{"PM -UX" LINK PM_Batch_CmdU}).

   You  can  insert  several @{"control characters" LINK Phrase} in order to customize the
   ReplyText.

   The total length of the text must be less than 1000 chr.

   When you press return, CPM will show you how your ReplyTXT will "look"
   in your message.


   Example:

   #REPLYTXT "Hi %f,\n\nI'm on Holiday!  I'll contact you A.S.A.P. !\n\n"

@ENDNODE ReplyTXT

@NODE Def_Logo "CPM: TEXT Configuration Window => Logo"

   [#LOGO "Text"]

   This parameter lets you define your own logo or signature.

   You  can  insert  several @{"control characters" LINK Phrase} in order to customize the
   logo.

   The total length of the text must be less than 245 chr.

   When  you press return, CPM will show you how your Logo will "look" in
   your message.


   Example:

   #LOGO "\nBest Regards,\nPino (2:335/602.2)\n"

@ENDNODE Def_Logo

@NODE Custom_Cfg_Window "CPM: CUSTOM Configuration Window"
@PREV "TextW"
@NEXT "SaveW"
@TOC "CPMMain"
   CUSTOM Configuration Window

   @{" Areas Window   " LINK Custom_Gadgets}   @{" Command Name   " LINK CMDName}   @{" Browse Window  " LINK CustomBrowse_Gadgets}
                      @{" Command        " LINK CMD}
                      @{" Command Type   " LINK CMDType}

@ENDNODE Custom_Cfg_Window

@NODE Custom_Gadgets "CPM: CUSTOM Configuration Window => Custom Gadgets"
@PREV "Custom_Cfg_Window"
@NEXT "CMDName"
@TOC "Custom_Cfg_Window"
   [#CUSTOM [DOS/SCRIPT/AREXX] num "text" "command"]

   PM  V3.21  lets you to configure 15 Custom gadgets (Menu Items) in the
   Areas  window.  When you want to use a gadget you have to click on the
   gadget to configure it.

   In  order  to  configure  a  Custom  gadget  you  have to click in the
   corresponding gadget in CPM and to fill in the needed parameters:

   @{"Command Name" LINK CMDName} - Is the string that will be shown inside the gadget

   @{"Command Type" LINK CMDType} - Select the type of command that you want to execute

   @{"Command" LINK CMD}      - The  command  that  you  want  to execute when you will
                  click on the gadget.


   Examples:

   #CUSTOM  DOS	0	"ConfigPM"	"MAIL:Bin/CPM"
   #CUSTOM  DOS	1	"Edit .CFG"	"C:Ed MAIL:PManager.CFG"
   #CUSTOM  DOS	2	"View Log"	"C:PPMore Logs:PM_Beta.Log"

@ENDNODE Custom_Gadgets

@NODE CustomBrowse_Gadgets "CPM: CUSTOM Configuration Window => Custom Gadgets"
@PREV "Custom_Cfg_Window"
@NEXT "CMDName"
@TOC "Custom_Cfg_Window"
   [#CUSTOMBROWSE [DOS/SCRIPT/AREXX] num "text" "command"]

   PM V3.21 lets you to configure 15 Custom gadgets in the Browse window.
   When  you  want  to  use  a  gadget you have to click on the gadget to
   configure it.

   In  order  to  configure  a  Custom  menu  you  have  to  click in the
   corresponding gadget in CPM and to fill in the needed parameters:

   @{"Command Name" LINK CMDName} - Is the string that will be shown inside the menu

   @{"Command Type" LINK CMDType} - Select the type of command that you want to execute

   @{"Command" LINK CMD}      - The  command  that  you  want  to execute when you will
                  select the menu item.


   Examples:

   #CUSTOMBROWSE  DOS	0	"Edit .MSG"	"C:ED %p%n.msg"
   #CUSTOMBROWSE  DOS	1	"NodeInfo"	"MAIL:Bin/NodeInfo %k"

@ENDNODE CustomBrowse_Gadgets

@NODE CMDName "CPM: CUSTOM Configuration Window => Command Name"
@NEXT "CMDType"
@TOC "Custom_Cfg_Window"
   Command Name

   Is the string that will be shown inside the gadget (up to 9 chr).

   You can customize up to 10 menu items.

@ENDNODE CMDName

@NODE CMDType "CPM: CUSTOM Configuration Window => Command Type"
@PREV "CMDName"
@NEXT "CMD"
@TOC "Custom_Cfg_Window"
   Command Type

   Select the type of command that you want to execute:

   DOS       - PM  will  pass  to the CLI the string you have inserted in
               the Command gadget.

   PM Script - Use  this  if  you have inserted in the Command Gadget the
               name of a @{"PM script file" LINK PMScript}.

   AREXX     - Not currently implemented.

@ENDNODE CMDType

@NODE CMD "CPM: CUSTOM Configuration Window => Command"
@PREV "CMDType"
@NEXT "Custom_Cfg_Window"
@TOC "Custom_Cfg_Window"
   Command

   Insert  here  the command that you want to execute when you will click
   on the gadget, or select the menu-item (from the Pull-Down menu).

   You  can  insert  several @{"control characters" LINK Phrase} in order to customize the
   the command.


   Examples:

   - "C:ED %p%n.msg"

      will load the current msg into your text editor.

   - "Run MAIL:Bin/TrapDoor call %?"

      will pop up a string requester where you can insert the node number
      you want to call.


   Of  course,  in  the  Areas  window not all the control characters are
   defined,  as  there  isn't a current message or a current area, so any
   control  characters  that  refer directly to a message or an area (for
   example %a or %D) will be ignored.

@ENDNODE CMD

@NODE SaveW "CPM: Save"
@PREV "Custom_Cfg_Window"
@NEXT "QuitW"
@TOC "CPMMain"
   Save

   You  can  use this gadget to Save your Config to PManager.CFG and Quit
   CPM.

@ENDNODE SaveW

@NODE QuitW "CPM: Quit"
@PREV "SaveW"
@NEXT "CPMMain"
@TOC "CPMMain"
   Quit

   You  can  use this gadget to Quit CPM, without saving the Config.  The
   CLOSEWINOW gadget does the same.

@ENDNODE QuitW

@NODE Phrase "Control Characters"
   In the phrase you can insert the following control characters:

      %a - Name of the area
      %b - Free Kb on device MAIL:
      %D - Date and Time of the original message
      %d - Date of the original message
      %F - Name [FROM] (Name and SurName)
      %f - Name [FROM] (Name)
      %H - The maximum amount of messages in the area
      %K - Complete Address of the sender (without Domain)
      %k - Address of the sender (without Point and Domain)
      %N - The amount of messages in the area
      %n - Number of the quoted message
      %p - Path of the area
      %r - Random number (0-100)
      %S - Subject of the message (All)
      %s - Subject of the message (First 20 characters)
      %T - Name [TO] (Name and SurName)
      %t - Name [TO] (Name)
      %X - Date and Time in FidoNet format of the present message
      %x - Date in FidoNet format of the present message
      %Y - Name [SYSOP] (Name and Surname)
      %? - Opens  a  string  requester  where you can enter the text that
           will replace the control character
      \n - Newline - Equals [ENTER]
      \q - quotations marks (")

@ENDNODE Phrase

@NODE Operation "Operation POINT MANAGER"
@PREV "Configuration"
@NEXT "Conclusion"
@TOC "Main"
   Operation

   We can divide the operation of Point Manager in four parts:

   @{" Interactive Session " LINK PMIntSes}
   @{" The BATCH Commands  " LINK PMBatch}
   @{" The SCRIPT Commands " LINK PMScript}
   @{" AREXX support       " LINK PMArexx}

@ENDNODE Operation

@NODE PMIntSes "POINT MANAGER - Interactive Session"

   You can launch PM in Interactive Mode with 'PM -W' or simply 'PM'

   If  everything is configured correctly, PM will open its Areas window.
   This is one (and first) of the three Windows.

   @{" AREAS Window             " LINK PMAreasW}   Select the Area(s)
   @{" MESSAGES Window          " LINK PMMessW}   Select the Message(s)
   @{" BROWSE Window            " LINK PM_Browse_Window}   Reading a Message
   @{" EDITOR Parameters Window " LINK Editor_Parameters}   Addressing of a Message

@ENDNODE PMIntSes

@NODE PMAreasW "AREAS Window"
@PREV "PMIntSes"
@NEXT "PMMessW"
@TOC "PMIntSes"
   Areas Window

   In this window, PM will display all the areas that you have defined in
   your Configuration file.  The window title bar will display the amount
   of  free  Chip  and  Fast  Ram  and  the  available space on the MAIL:
   volume.

   @{" Areas List         " LINK PM_AreaListBox}   The AreaList Box
   @{" Gadgets            " LINK PM_Area_Gadgets}   The Gadgets of the Area Window
   @{" Pull-Down Menu     " LINK PD_Menu_AreasWindow}   The Pull-Down Menu
   @{" Keyboard Shortcuts " LINK Areas_Window_Shortkeys}   The Hotkeys of the Menus/Gadgets

@ENDNODE PMAreasW

@NODE PM_AreaListBox "Areas List"
   Areas List

   For every Area, PM will give you the following information:

    Area   : Area Name.

    NMsg   : Total number of messages in the area.

    HiMsg  : The number of the newest message.

    Space  : The  space in KiloBytes, that the area occupies.  If you use
             @{"Index" LINK PMIndex},  this  information  is  not available (except after a
             @{"DeepScan" LINK PMDScan} action, selected manually or after a crash).

    X      : This is the 'Delete by/Renumber by' criterion:
             D=Date  N=Number. (see @{"Delete By" LINK Delete_By}).

    NDel   : The number of messages that will be left by @{"DELETE" LINK PMDel}.
             (see @{"Num. of Messages" LINK Number_Of_Msg}).

    Status : Area Status.


   The Status field gives a lot of extra information.  It is a 6 chr long
   string, This is the meaning of each chr:

    1 chr:  Type of area (M=matrix, E=Echo, B=Bad)

    2 chr:  Range (I=international, N=National, H=Hub, L=Local)

    3 chr:  Read-Status (S=Scanned, D=DeepScanned)

    4 chr:  Read-Mode (R=Read-Only)

    5 chr:  Import-Status (I=Imported area, N=New messages, S=Sysop news)

    6 chr:  Export-Status (E=Area with Un-Exported messages)

@ENDNODE PM_AreaListBox

@NODE PM_Area_Gadgets "Gadgets"
   Gadgets

   On  the  left  side  of  the  Areas  list you will find two columns of
   gadgets.

   The  leftmost  is  reserved  for PM internal functions.  The second is
   available for Custom gadgets defined by you in the configuration file.

   These are PM's internal Gadgets and Custom Gadgets:

    Internal      Custom
   @{" Scan     " LINK PMScan}    @{"  Define  " LINK Custom_Gadgets}
   @{" DeepScan " LINK PMDScan}    @{"   your   " LINK Custom_Gadgets}
   @{" Delete   " LINK PMDel}    @{"   own    " LINK Custom_Gadgets}
   @{" Safe Del " LINK PMSafeDel}    @{"  CUSTOM  " LINK Custom_Gadgets}
   @{" Renum    " LINK PMRenum}    @{" Gadgets  " LINK Custom_Gadgets}
   @{" Update   " LINK PMUpdate}    @{"          " LINK Custom_Gadgets}
   @{" Free     " LINK PMFree}    @{"          " LINK Custom_Gadgets}
   @{" Info     " LINK PMInfo}    @{"          " LINK Custom_Gadgets}
   @{" Poll     " LINK PMPoll}    @{"          " LINK Custom_Gadgets}
   @{" Import   " LINK PMImport}    @{"          " LINK Custom_Gadgets}
   @{" Export   " LINK PMExport}    @{"          " LINK Custom_Gadgets}
   @{" All      " LINK PMAll}    @{"          " LINK Custom_Gadgets}
   @{" Clear    " LINK PMClear}    @{"          " LINK Custom_Gadgets}


   A  special  gadget  is  the  'Zoom' Gadget, which is really an Iconify
   Gadget.   You can find it over the scroll gadget.  This will close the
   Areas Window and create a little Icon instead.

@ENDNODE PM_Area_Gadgets

@NODE PD_Menu_AreasWindow "Pull-Down Menu Areas Window"
@PREV "PM_Area_Gadgets"
@NEXT "Areas_Window_Shortkeys"
@TOC "PMAreasW"
   Pull-Down Menu Areas Window

   These are the menu entries in the Areas Window:


   Project Menu      System Menu

   @{" About         " LINK PMAbout}   @{" Restore Bad Messages " LINK PMRestBMes}
                     @{" File Request         " LINK PMFileReq}
   @{" Edit CFG      " LINK PMCfgPM}   @{" File Send            " LINK PMFileSnd}
   @{" Load CFG      " LINK PMRelCfg}   @{" Change Palette       " LINK PMCPalette}
                     @{" Kill Index           " LINK PMKIndex}
   @{" Quit PM       " LINK PMQuit}   @{" Kill Statistics      " LINK PMKStats}


@ENDNODE PD_Menu_AreasWindow

@NODE PMScan "Scan"
   Scan

   This  gadget  will  scan  all  the areas, updating their status in the
   areas list.

   If  you  have  selected @{"HoldMem" LINK HoldMem}, it will also load into memory all the
   information about messages in the areas.

@ENDNODE PMScan

@NODE PMDScan "DeepScan"
   DeepScan

   This  gadget  will Scan the selected Areas in a deeper way and totally
   rebuild the Index and Statistics files.

   It can be really slower than Scan but it will be useful when the Index
   and/or  the  Statistics  files  have become corrupted or are incorrect
   (use it, for example, after a Crash).

@ENDNODE PMDScan

@NODE PMDel "Delete"
   Delete

   This gadget will Delete messages from the selected Areas.

   The  delete command will not affect protected messages and will leave
   at least @{"'NDel'" LINK PM_AreaListBox 15} messages in the selected areas.  The delete criterion
   is that written in @{"'X'" LINK PM_AreaListBox 12}.

@ENDNODE PMDel

@NODE PMSafeDel "Safe Delete"
   Safe Del

   This  gadget  is like the @{"Delete gadget" LINK PMDel}, but this won't delete un-read
   new messages.

@ENDNODE PMSafeDel

@NODE PMRenum "Renum"
   Renum

   This gadget will Renumber messages in the selected Areas.

   It  will  reorder  messages following the @{"'X'" LINK PM_AreaListBox 11} criterion.  It will also
   perform a 'Clean Up' of the area.

@ENDNODE PMRenum

@NODE PMUpdate "Update"
   Update

   This  gadget will Update the Index and Statistic files.  It is useful,
   for example, after an @{"Import" LINK PMImport}.

@ENDNODE PMUpdate

@NODE PMFree "Free"
   Free

   This  gadget  will  Free  the memory allocated for the selected Areas.
   (This could be useful in memory panic situations).

   It will also updates the Index files of the selected areas.

@ENDNODE PMFree

@NODE PMInfo "Info"
   Info

   This  gadget has two functions.  If there is no area selected, it will
   display an histogram with the amount of messages imported and exported
   for every area.

   If  there  are  some  areas selected, it will display some information
   about those areas, like:


            Area : Matrix.MAUI

        Imported Msg         :    30  Last  :     0
        Imported Msg (Sysop) :    27  Last  :     0
        Exported Msg         :    38  Last  :     1
        First Import on  06 Feb 93  11:54:11
        Last  Import on  06 Apr 93  23:12:44
        First Export on  04 Feb 93  23:59:43
        Last  Export on  06 Apr 93  00:19:32
        PM activity index on this area : 3191
        PM Interactivity index on area :  71

@ENDNODE PMInfo

@NODE PMPoll "Poll"
   Poll

   This  gadget  will  launch the command you have specified as @{"Mailer" LINK Mailer} in
   your configuration.

@ENDNODE PMPoll

@NODE PMImport "Import"
   Import

   This gadget will Import all the bundles in your @{"Inbound" LINK Inbound} dir.

@ENDNODE PMImport

@NODE PMExport "Export"
   Export

   This  gadget will Export messages from the selected areas (and PM will
   put them in your @{"Outbound" LINK Outbound} directory).

@ENDNODE PMExport

@NODE PMAll "All"
   All

   This gadget will select all the areas.

@ENDNODE PMAll

@NODE PMClear "Clear"
   Clear

   This gadget will deselect all the areas.

@ENDNODE PMClear

@NODE PMAbout "About"
   About

   This shows a Window with the name and version of this program, and the
   name of the Author(s).

@ENDNODE PMAbout

@NODE PMCfgPM "Edit CFG"
   Edit CFG

   This will launch @{"CPM" LINK CPMMain} (if it is in the system path), so you can
   (re-)configure the config file.

@ENDNODE PMCfgPM

@NODE PMRelCfg "Load CFG"
   Load CFG

   This   will  reload  the  configuration  file  (PManager.CFG)  without
   quitting PM.

   LAYOUT CHANGES WON'T WORK correctly.  If you have changed something in
   the Layout window of CPM, you need to quit and re-run PM.

@ENDNODE PMRelCfg

@NODE PMQuit "Quit PM"
   Quit PM

   This  will  result  in  Closing  the  Main-Window  of  PM,  opening  a
   "Wait-Window",  updating  the Index- and Statistics-files (which could
   take  a while), releasing all its used memory, and finally closing the
   "Wait-Window" (and Screen when used).

@ENDNODE PMQuit

@NODE PMRestBMes "Restore Bad Messages"
   Restore Bad Messages

   This  entry  will  rescue  messages that have been sent to @{"BAD" LINK CheckDupe}, either
   because  the  area  did  not exist or if another error was encountered
   during @{"IMPORT" LINK PMImport}.

@ENDNODE PMRestBMes

@NODE PMFileReq "File Request"
   File Request

   Opens  a window where you can specify which files you want to Request,
   and from where. The address format is zone:net/node.

@ENDNODE PMFileReq

@NODE PMFileSnd "File Send"
   File Send

   Opens a window where you can specify which files you want to Send, and
   where. The address format is zone:net/node.

@ENDNODE PMFileSnd

@NODE PMCPalette "Change Palette"
   Change Palette

   This  menu-item  will  open  a  Palette  Requester,  so you can change
   (temporarely) the colors, used by PM.

@ENDNODE PMCPalette

@NODE PMKIndex "Kill Index"
   Kill Index

   This entry will delete the @{"Index" LINK PMIndex} files of the selected areas.

   WARNING: Use this only if you know what you are doing.

@ENDNODE PMKIndex

@NODE PMKStats "Kill Stats"
   Kill Stats

   This entry will delete the Statistic files of the selected areas.

   WARNING: Use this only if you know what you are doing.

@ENDNODE PMKStats

@NODE Areas_Window_Shortkeys "Areas Window Keyboard Shortcuts"
   
   This are the keyboard shortcuts available in the Areas Window:

    Amiga+?             -  About
    Amiga+E             -  Edit CFG
    Amiga+L             -  Load CFG
    Amiga+Q             -  Quit PM
    Amiga+B             -  Restore Bad Messages
    Amiga+F             -  File Request
    Amiga+S             -  File Send
    Amiga+C             -  Change Palette
    Help                -  Open the PM commands window
    Up Arrow            -  Scroll up one line
    Shift + Up Arrow    -  Scroll up one page
    Down Arrow          -  Scroll down one line
    Shift + Down Arrow  -  Scroll down one page

@ENDNODE Areas_Window_Shortkeys

@NODE PMMessW "MESSAGES Window"
@PREV "PMAreasW"
@NEXT "PM_Browse_Window"
@TOC "PMIntSes"
   Messages Window

   When  you  double-click  on an area PM will scan the area and open the
   MESSAGE window

   The  messages  window  is divided into two parts.  The first shows you
   the messages available in the area and the second displays a series of
   gadgets, to which different functions are assigned.

   @{" Messages List      " LINK PMMList}   The Message List Box
   @{" Gadgets            " LINK PMMWGad}   The Gadgets of the Message Window
   @{" Keyboard Shortcuts " LINK PMMWKShort}   The Hotkeys of the Menus/Gadgets

@ENDNODE PMMessW

@NODE PMMList "Message List"
   Message List

   For every message PM will display the following information:

    - Date
    - Subject
    - From
    - To
    - Status

   The Status field gives a lot of extra information.  It is a 6 chr long
   string, This is the meaning of each chr:

    1 chr   : N = New message, S = Sysop news

    2 chr   : M = Marked

    3 chr   : P = Protected from deletion

    4 chr   : S = Exported (SENT)

    5 chr   : D = To be DELETED

    6 chr   : A = PM  has already answered to this msg with the @{"AutoReply" LINK PM_Batch_CmdU}
                  function

@ENDNODE PMMList

@NODE PMMWGad "Messages Window Gadgets"
   Gadgets

    All         Select ALL messages

    Clear       Deselect ALL messages

    S News      Select ALL the NEW messages

    Search      Search and Select messages that meet the params entered.

    Read        Lets you READ ALL the SELECTED messages.

    Write       Lets you @{"WRITE" LINK Editor_Parameters} a message.

    Reply       Lets you @{"REPLY" LINK Editor_Parameters} to the selected message(s).

    Forward     Opens  a  window where you can  select the area where you
                want to @{"FORWARD" LINK Editor_Parameters} the selected message(s).

    XReply      Opens  a  window where you can  select the area where you
                want to send your reply to the selected message(s).

    Edit        Lets you @{"EDIT" LINK Editor_Parameters} the selected message(s).

    Archive     ARCHIVES all selected messages(s).

    Print       PRINTS all selected messages(s).

    Delete      Set DELETE flag for all selected messages.

    Ed Flags    Lets you edit the flags of the selected messages. You can
                also select messages with specified flags.

    Additive    Select  this  if  you  want to select messages that match
                with different Search parameters.

    Sort        Type here the Message sort criteria (you can use the same
                parameters used for @{"MsgOrder" LINK MsgOrder}.  When you press return,  PM
                will  Resort the messages following the new sort criteria
                (It  is  possible  to  insert  more  than  one  parameter
                simultaneously).

@ENDNODE PMMWGad

@NODE PMMWKShort "Messages Window Keyboard Shortcuts"

   This are the keyboard shortcuts available in the Messages Window:

    Q / Esc             -  Back to Areas Window
    Amiga+F             -  File Request
    N                   -  Jump to next Area with new messages
    R                   -  Read selected messages
    S                   -  Select New messages
    W                   -  @{"Write" LINK Editor_Parameters} a message
    Up Arrow            -  Scroll up one line
    Shift + Up Arrow    -  Scroll up one page
    Ctrl + Up Arrow     -  Jump to the first page
    Down Arrow          -  Scroll down one line
    Shift + Down Arrow  -  Scroll down one page
    Ctrl + Down Arrow   -  Jump to the last page


   You can also read a message by double-clicking.

   When you return to the Areas window, PM will check if you have flagged
   any  messages  for DELETE and asks you to confirm this.  If you answer
   'Yes' PM will delete the flagged messages.

@ENDNODE PMMWKShort

@NODE Editor_Parameters "Editor Parameters Window"
   Editor Parameters Window

   When  @{"writing" LINK PMMWGad 13},  @{"replying" LINK PMMWGad 15}, @{"forwarding" LINK PMMWGad 17}, @{"editing" LINK PMMWGad 23} a message, a window will
   pop-up,  named  "Editor Parameters" (well actually after quitting your
   editor),  where  you  can enter the name and address of the addressee,
   subject  of  the  message,  etc.,  and  select  some attributes and/or
   options.

   There are two (slightly) different windows:

   @{" Parameters Window NetMail  " LINK ED_Parameter_Netmail}
   @{" Parameters Window EchoMail " LINK ED_Parameter_Echomail}

@ENDNODE Editor_Parameters

@NODE Ed_Parameter_Netmail "Parameters Window NetMail"

   The  following  Editor  Parameters  Window will be shown when writing,
   replying or forwarding a Netmail (AKA Matrix) message:


          Editor Parameters Window (for Matrix/Netmail Areas)

      From: [Your Username]      [Your Point-address]
      To  : [Username Addressee] [Node/Point-address]
      Subj: [Subject of Message]

        o  @{"Private     " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 4}      o  @{"Kill Sent  " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 24}     @{"   OK   " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 33}
        o  @{"Crash       " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 7}      o  @{"Matrix RR  " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 26}     @{"  Edit  " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 35}
        o  @{"File Attach " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 11}      o  @{"Reflow Msg " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 31}     @{" Cancel " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 37}
        o  @{"Hold        " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 21}      -  .....



        o = available 
        - = not available (ghosted)

   The   From:   name  is  taken  from  the  @{"#SYSOP" LINK Sysop}  parameter  and  your
   Point-Address  behind  it,  is  derived from the NetMail-Area your are
   working in, thus the related @{"#AREA" LINK Cfg_Echo_Area} parameter of your PManager.CFG.  If
   needed,  you  can always change this name and/or address (manually) to
   suit your needs!

   The  To:   field  will  be  filled  with the name of the author of the
   message  you're  replying to, or the same name/address of the original
   addressee  when editing a message.  Both fields will be empty when you
   start to write a new message.

   The  Subj:   field  contains  the  subject of the message.  In case of
   replying  to  a message, PM will put "RE:  " before the original text,
   so  it's obvious that it's a reply to an original message/subject.  If
   this "RE:  " is already there, PM will leave it alone.  When writing a
   new  message,  this  field  will  be  empty, but you'll have to use an
   appropriate subject that covers the contents of the message.

   P.S. If  the  contents  of  your  message  doesn't cover  the  subject
        (anymore), please change it to an appropriate one.

   @{" Parameters Window Flags & Buttons    " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags}
   @{" Parameters Window Keyboard Shortcuts " LINK Ed_Parameter_Shortcuts}

@ENDNODE Ed_Parameter_Netmail

@NODE Ed_Parameter_Echomail "Parameters Window EchoMail"

   The  following  Editor  Parameters  Window will be shown when writing,
   replying, forwarding a Echomail message:


          Editor Parameters Window (for Echo-Areas)

      From: [Your Username]
      To  : [Username Addressee]
      Subj: [Subject of Message]
      Orig: [Origin  of Message]

        o  @{"Private     " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 4}      o  @{"Kill Sent  " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 24}     @{"   OK   " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 33}
        o  @{"Crash       " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 7}      -  @{"Matrix RR  " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 26}     @{"  Edit  " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 35}
        -  @{"File Attach " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 11}      o  @{"Reflow Msg " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 31}     @{" Cancel " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 37}
        -  @{"Hold        " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags 21}      -  .....



        o = available 
        - = not available (ghosted)

   The   From:   name  is  taken  from  the  @{"#SYSOP" LINK Sysop}  parameter  and  your
   Point-Address  behind  it,  is  derived  from  the  Echo-Area your are
   working in, thus the related @{"#AREA" LINK Cfg_Echo_Area} parameter of your PManager.CFG.  If
   needed,  you  can always change this name and/or address (manually) to
   suit your needs!

   The  To:   field  will  be  filled  with the name of the author of the
   message you're replying to, or the same name of the original addressee
   when  editing  a  message.  This field will be empty when you start to
   write  a  new  message.   When writing in a message without specifying
   someones  name,  you  should  use  "All"  (without quotes) in stead of
   leaving it blank.

   The  Subj:   field  contains  the  subject of the message.  In case of
   replying  to  a message, PM will put "RE:  " before the original text,
   so  it's obvious that it's a reply to an original message/subject.  If
   this "RE:  " is already there, PM will leave it alone.  When writing a
   new  message,  this  field  will  be  empty, but you'll have to use an
   appropriate subject that covers the contents of the message.

   P.S. If  the  contents  of  your  message  doesn't  cover  the subject
        (anymore), please change it to an appropriate one.

   The Orig:  field (Origin) is derrived either from the #AREAORIGIN when
   defined, or #ORIGIN, which is the default string.

   @{" Parameters Window Flags & Buttons    " LINK Ed_Parameter_Flags}
   @{" Parameters Window Keyboard Shortcuts " LINK Ed_Parameter_Shortcuts}


@ENDNODE Ed_Parameter_Echomail

@NODE Ed_Parameter_Flags "Parameters Window Flags/Buttons"

   Explanation of the various flags/buttons:

   Private    : Message  will be marked as Private.  Remember, Netmail is
                always Private and Echomail is always Public.

   Crash      : Means  that  the  message  should be sent directly to the
                Addressee  (for  example,  in  case  of  important mail),
                instead of routed to your Boss.

   File Attach: A  file  will  be sent along with this (netmail) message.
                After  selecting this gadget, a File-Requester will open,
                where you can select the file you want to be transferred.
                Name  of  the  file  will be in the Subject field of this
                message.   Remember  that  file-attaches  will  never  be
                routed.  If it should be sent to a user at an other place
                as  your  Boss,  select  the Crash button too (you should
                bring   the  message  and  file  yourself  at  the  right
                Node/BBS).

   Hold       : This  message will be placed on Hold, and will be sent if
                the receiver calls you.

   Kill Sent  : Message will be killed (deleted) after Export.

   Matrix RR  : Receipt  Request,  which  means that the addressee should
                (automatically) return an acknowledge message back to you
                if  he  has  received  your  message (the other site must
                support this!).

   Reflow Msg : When selected, PM will @{"reflow" LINK Reflow} your message-text.

   OK         : Acknowledge posting/writing actions.

   EDIT       : Edit current message.

   CANCEL     : Abort posting/writing.


@ENDNODE Ed_Parameter_Flags

@NODE Ed_Parameter_Shortcuts "Parameters Window Keyboard Shortcuts"

   These  are  the  keyboard shortcuts available in the Editor Parameters
   Window:

    Amiga+O             - OK
    Right Mouse-Button  - OK
    Amiga+E             - EDIT
    Amiga+C             - CANCEL
    ESC                 - CANCEL
    Return              - Activates the To: Gadget

@ENDNODE Ed_Parameter_Shortcuts

@NODE PM_Browse_Window "BROWSE Window"
@PREV "PMMessW"
@TOC "PMIntSes"
   Messages are displayed in this window.

   In  the  title  bar,  you  will  find the Area Name, the number of the
   message  you  are currently reading, its lenghth, the number of Unread
   messages  (it  counts  the  number  of  selected messages with the NEW
   flag), and 10 small @{"gadgets" LINK Msg_Browse_Win_Gads}.

   From   this  version   there  is  also  a  @{"Custom Menu" LINK CustomBrowse_Gadgets}  with  all  the
   CustomBrowse  commands.   If you release the Right Mouse-Button on the
   menu,  PM  will  run the selected custom command, otherwise it will go
   back in the Message Window (if @{"ExitDMouse" LINK ExitDM} is active).

   There are also @{"Keyboard Shortcuts" LINK Msg_Browse_Win_Shortkeys} available.

@ENDNODE PM_Browse_Window

@NODE Msg_Browse_Win_Gads "Messages Browse Window Gadgets"
   Messages Browse Window Gadgets

    W  -  @{"Write" LINK Editor_Parameters} a message
    R  -  @{"Reply" LINK Editor_Parameters} to a message
    X  -  @{"Cross Reply" LINK Editor_Parameters} to a message
    E  -  @{"Edit" LINK Editor_Parameters} a message
    D  -  Delete a message
    P  -  Print a message
    A  -  Archive a message
    K  -  Protect a message
    F  -  File Request
    G  -  @{"Forward" LINK Editor_Parameters} a message

   @{" Keyboard Shortcuts " LINK Msg_Browse_Win_Shortkeys}

@ENDNODE Msg_Browse_Win_Gads

@NODE Msg_Browse_Win_Shortkeys "Browse Window Keyboard Shortcuts"

   This are the keyboard shortcuts available in the Browse Window:

    Q / Esc             -  Back to the MESSAGE Window
    Up Arrow            -  Scroll up one line
    Shift + Up Arrow    -  Scroll up one page
    Ctrl + Up Arrow     -  Jump to the first page
    Down Arrow          -  Scroll down one line
    Shift + Down Arrow  -  Scroll down one page
    Ctrl + Down Arrow   -  Jump to the last page
    Right Arrow         -  Next selected message
    Shift + Right Arrow -  Next message
    Alt + Right Arrow   -  Next message in the thread
    Left Arrow          -  Previous selected message
    Shift + Left Arrow  -  Previous message
    Alt + Left Arrow    -  Previous message in the thread

    W                   -  @{"Write" LINK Editor_Parameters} a message
    R                   -  @{"Reply" LINK Editor_Parameters} to a message
    X                   -  @{"Cross Reply" LINK Editor_Parameters} to a message
    E                   -  @{"Edit" LINK Editor_Parameters} a message
    D                   -  Delete a message
    Del                 -  Delete a message and read the next
    P                   -  Print a message
    A                   -  Archive a message
    K                   -  Protect a message
    F                   -  File Request
    G                   -  @{"Forward" LINK Editor_Parameters} a message
    T                   -  Open a new PM AREAS window
                           (the current BROWSE window remains frozen)
    H                   -  Hide/Show kludges
    M                   -  Mark a message
    N                   -  Jump to next Area with new messages


   From  v3.21  you can use also KeyPad controls  (Up, Down, Left, Right,
   PgUp,  PgDn,  Home,  End).  You  can also use the 'Space' key:  if you
   are  reading  a  msg, 'space' scrolls down one page, at the end of the
   msg  it goes to the next selected msg, at the end of the selected msgs
   it goes back to the Messages Window.

   If  you  press  the  Left Mouse-Button  with the pointer placed in the
   Right-Middle of the screen, PM will display the next message.

   If  you  click  in  the  Left-Middle of the screen PM will display the
   previous message.

   On  the  other  hand,  if you wish to scroll up or down in the current
   message,  you  should place the point either above or below the middle
   of the screen.

@ENDNODE Msg_Browse_Win_Shortkeys

@NODE PMBatch "POINT MANAGER - Batch Commands"
   The BATCH commands

   The  BATCH  commands  are  the  typical commands that you will find in
   almost  any  other  Tosser/Scanner, even though PM has some additional
   commands that you probably haven't encountered before.  These commands
   are  normally  executed  in  connection  with either IMPORT, EXPORT or
   MAINT of messages.

   Many of these operations can be executed in INTERACTIVE mode.

   These are some examples of BATCH commands:

    PM -L        LIST information about all areas
    PM -RDPIPPO  RENUMBER all messages in the area named PIPPO by DATE
    PM -I        Do an IMPORT.

   With  PM  you  can  enter  multiple  commands  into a SCRIPT file, and
   execute the commands in the SCRIPT file via PM.

   When you execute more than one command in a CLI, the commands will not
   necessarily  be  executed  in  the  order  they where entered in.  The
   reason  being  that  PM has a built-in security that prevents you from
   performing 'WRONG' tasks.

   This  is  the order in which PM will execute multiple orders in one PM
   command line :

   @{" -?  " LINK PM_Batch_Cmd?}     Help Screen
   @{" -#  " LINK PM_Batch_Cmd#}     System Info
   @{" -F  " LINK PM_Batch_CmdF}     Specify Config file
   @{" -UT " LINK PM_Batch_CmdU}     Turbolize
   @{" -UQ " LINK PM_Batch_CmdU}     Quick Message Writer
   @{" -UK " LINK PM_Batch_CmdU}     Kill Statistics
   @{" -UR " LINK PM_Batch_CmdU}     Request File
   @{" -US " LINK PM_Batch_CmdU}     Send File
   @{" -UX " LINK PM_Batch_CmdU}     Autoreply Utility
   @{" -UD " LINK PM_Batch_CmdU}     Dos Processor Utility
   @{" -L  " LINK PM_Batch_CmdL}     List Areas
   @{" -P  " LINK PM_Batch_CmdP}     Print
   @{" -E  " LINK PM_Batch_CmdE}     Export
   @{" -A  " LINK PM_Batch_CmdA}     Archive
   @{" -B  " LINK PM_Batch_CmdB}     Salvage Bad
   @{" -D  " LINK PM_Batch_CmdD}     Delete
   @{" -R  " LINK PM_Batch_CmdR}     Renum
   @{" -I  " LINK PM_Batch_CmdI}     Import
   @{" -W  " LINK PM_Batch_CmdW}     INTERACTIVE session
   @{" -C  " LINK PM_Batch_CmdC}     Script Command Processor

   The  description of the BATCH-command syntax will be done by using '['
   and  ']'  to  enclose  the  OPTIONAL parameters and the '{' and '}' to
   enclose  COMPULSIVE  parameters  of BATCH-commands and the '/' will be
   used to separate the various options.

@ENDNODE PMBatch

@NODE PM_Batch_Cmd? "Batch Command -?"
   The -? command (Help Screen)

   Syntax: PM -?

   Display the Point Manager help screen, like:


    Point Manager : MAIL UTILITY  Ver. 3.21/g   Rel. 561 (Mar 29 1993)
   Copyright © 1992,93  by Pino Aliberti      ( 2:335/602.2 )
   Copyright © 1990,91  by Mario Pacchiarotti ( 2:335/320.0 )
   All rights reserved


   PM [-E[area]] [-L[area]] [-P[area][#number]] [-F{file}]
      [-V[level]] [-R[D/N][!area]] [-I[?]] [-X[HlNlQlSlC]] [-?]
      [-D[D/N][number][!area]] [-O{NlDlSlFlT}] [-C[scriptfile]]
      [-A[area][#asd] [-B[area]] [-W[area]] [-U{R/S/Qarea/T[area]}/K/X]

      -? Write this help screen

      -A archive [a]all [s]sysop [d]deleted message of [area]
      -B restore Bad Message of [area]
      -C use command [scriptfile]
      -D delete messages by [D/N] Date or Number in [area]
      -E export one [area] or all
      -F specify config file name
      -I import messages or [?] list only
      -L list [area] informations
      -N read all news in message base
      -O specify order criteria for messages list
      -P print on video the message in [area]
      -R renumber by [D/N] Date or Number one [area] or all
      -U Call PM internal Utilities (read documentation)
      -V Log Level [level]
      -X set some flags (read documentation)
      -W call interactive window Point Manager
   End PM - Elapsed Time   0:06

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_Cmd?

@NODE PM_Batch_Cmd# "Batch Command -#"
   The -# command (System Info)

   Syntax: PM -#

   Displays some internal (debugging) information, like:


    Point Manager : MAIL UTILITY  Ver. 3.21/g   Rel. 561 (Mar  29 1993)
   Copyright © 1992,93  by Pino Aliberti      ( 2:335/602.2 )
   Copyright © 1990,91  by Mario Pacchiarotti ( 2:335/320.0 )
   All rights reserved

   *** PM Internal Information

       - Real Release   :    561
       - Serial Number  :     15
       - MailPrefs size :   9894
       - MailArea  size :    188
       - ShortMsg  size :    110
       - Stack     size :  12000
       - Video Mode     :    PAL
       - Exec Softver   :    175
       - Processor      :  68000
       - CoProcessor    :     No
       - PowerFrequency :     50
       - CLI            : 526521
   End PM - Elapsed Time   0:10


   When  reporting  problems  to the author, please add this also to your
   report!

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_Cmd#

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdA "Batch Command -A"
   The -A command (Archive)

   Syntax: PM -A[area][#{a/s/d}]

   ARCHIVE  the  message(s)  in  the  specified  area,  according  to the
   following rules:

    #a  ARCHIVE all messages in the specified area

    #s  ARCHIVE all messages to and from SYSOP (You)

    #d  ARCHIVE all messages  DELETED with  -D command issued AT THE SAME
        TIME !

   The 3 parameters are mutually exclusive.

   Examples:

    PM -AAMIGA#a   ARCHIVE all messages in area AMIGA

    PM -A#d -DD    ARCHIVE all messages DELETED by the -DD command,issued
                   AT THE SAME TIME !

    PM -A#s        ARCHIVE all messages to and from SYSOP (You)

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdA

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdB "Batch Command -B"
   The -B command  (Restore/Salvage Bad)

   Syntax: PM -B[area]

   This  command  rescues  messages  that  have  been sent to BAD, either
   because  the  area  did  not exist or if another error was encountered
   during  IMPORT.   You  can  salvage either all BAD messages or specify
   which area's messages you want to rescue.

   Examples:

   PM -B          salvage all messages for all areas

   PM -BAMIGA     salvage all messages for area AMIGA

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdB

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdC "Batch Command -C"
   The -C command (Script Command Processor)

   Syntax: PM -C[filename]

   This  option  lets  you use a SCRIPT file containing multiple commands
   that PM should execute, so instead of having to enter them separately,
   you can edit a text once, and use this file henceforth.

   The  SCRIPT  file  commands  and their syntax will be described in the
   following chapter.

   Examples:

   PM -CPIPPO     Execute the SCRIPT file named PIPPO

   PM -Cram:zz    Execute the SCRIPT file named zz,  which  is located in
                  ram:

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdC

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdD "Batch Command -D"
   The -D command (Delete)

   Syntax: PM -D[D/N][number][!area]

   DELETEs  selected  messages, either by DATE or NUMBER, in all areas or
   in  a  specific  area.   Please  bear in mind that if you execute this
   command  from  the CLI, not all messages will be DELETEd, because some
   messages  may  be  protected  from DELETE.  These messages can only be
   DELETEd if you enter PM with -W option and remove the protection bit.

   Examples:

   PM -DN100      DELETE messages by NUMBER in all areas,  and  leave 100
                  messages untouched after DELETE

   PM -D          DELETE messages in all areas,  remembering  the ndelete
                  and sort parameter defined in #AREA (PManager.CFG)

   PM -DD!AMIGA   DELETE messages in  area AMIGA  by  DATE,  leaving  the
                  newest messages untouched after DELETE


   See also the @{"SCRIPT's DELETE" LINK PM_Script_Del} command.

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdD

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdE "Batch Command -E"
   The -E command (Export)

   Syntax: PM -E[area]

   Performs  an  EXPORT  and stores the produced packets in your OutBound
   directory.

   Examples:

   PM -E               perform an EXPORT of all areas

   PM -EAMIGA          perform an EXPORT of area AMIGA only

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdE

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdF "Batch Command -F"
   The -F command (Specify Config file)

   Syntax: PM -Ffilename

   Run  PM  with  the  specified config file.  With -F you MUST use -W in
   order to start PM in Interactive mode

   Examples:

   PM -Fother.CFG -W           run PM with other.CFG file

   PM -Fdh0:goofy.CFG -W       run PM with dh0:goofy.CFG config file

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdF

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdI "Batch Command -I"
   The -I command (Import)

   Syntax: PM -I[?]

   Performs an IMPORT of all packets in your Inbound directory.

   If you use the '?' option, it will only simulate the IMPORT.

   Examples:

   PM -I          perform an IMPORT

   PM -I?         simulate an IMPORT

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdI

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdL "Batch Command -L"
   The -L command (List Areas)

   Syntax: PM -L[area]

   This  command produces information of the area(s) listed.  You can use
   wildcards.  If no area is specified, all areas will be LISTed.

   Examples:

   PM -LAMIGA   produces information about the area called AMIGA

   PM -LPARA*   produces information about the areas starting  with  PARA
                (PARAgon, PARAchute etc.)

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdL

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdO "Batch Command -O"
   The -O command (Order)

   Syntax: PM -O{[f][t][s][d][n]}

   ORDER  messages  as  specified,  this  command overrides what you have
   specified in your configuration file.

   The possible parameters are:

    f   Sort by [FROM]
    t   Sort by [TO]
    s   Sort by [SUBJECT]
    d   Sort by [DATE]
    n   Sort by [MESSAGE-NUMBER]

   Examples:

   PM -Osd        SORT messages by SUBJECT and DATE

   PM -Ofd        SORT messages by FROM and DATE

   PM -On         SORT messages by NUMBER

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdO

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdP "Batch Command -P"
   The -P command (Print)

   Syntax: PM -P[area][#number]

   This command will PRINT the message(s) you specify either on screen or
   on the printer.

   Examples:

   PM -PAMIGA#123      print message 123 from area AMIGA on screen

   PM -P*#200          print message 200 from all areas on screen

   PM >PRT: -PLOGO     print all messages from area LOGO on printer

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdP

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdR "Batch Command -R"
   The -R command (Renum)

   Syntax: PM -R{D/N}[area]

   Performs  a  RENUMBER of the specified area.  You can also specify how
   PM  should  order  the  messages after the renumber is complete, which
   will  override  the  @{"MsgOrder" LINK MsgOrder}  you have specified in the configuration
   file.

   Examples:

   PM -RDAMIGA         RENUMBER area AMIGA by DATE

   PM -RN              RENUMBER all areas by NUMBER

   PM -RDP*            RENUMBER all areas starting with P by DATE

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdR

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdU "Batch Command -U"
   The -U command (Internal Utilities)

   Syntax: PM -U{R/S/Qarea/K/T[area]/X/D}

   Executes one of PM's internal utilities.


    R - Request File

   Opens  a  window  where  you  can  specify which file you wish to File
   Request, and from where (The format is zone:net/node).


    S - Send File

   Opens  a  window  which is identical to the previous, except that this
   window lets you specify which file you wish to send.


    Q - Quick Message Writer

   Opens PM's internal Text-Editor.  The parameter [area] is COMPULSIVE.


    K - KILL area statistics

   Erase/Reset area statistics for all areas.


    T[area] - Enable area for TURBOSCAN

   Modifies all messages for using PM with the TurboScan option.  This is
   only necessary if the messages were NOT IMPORTED with PM.


    X - Run the automatic reply utility

   PM  will  automatically reply to all messages in matrix areas.  Useful
   when sysop is on vacation...

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdU

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdV "Batch Command -V"
   The -V command (Log Level)

   Syntax: PM -V[level]

   Sets  the verbosity level of PM.  This overrides the LogLevel value in
   your configuration file.

   Examples:

   PM -V1         sets level 1

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdV

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdW "Batch Command -W"
   The -W command (Interactive Window)

   Syntax: PM -W[area]

   This  Activates  PM  in @{"INTERACTIVE mode" LINK PMIntSes}.  You can get the same effect
   starting PM without parameters.

   If area is specified, PM will open in the BROWSE window of that area.

   Example:

   PM -W          Execute PM in INTERACTIVE mode

   PM -WAMIGA     Start browsing area AMIGA

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdW

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdX "Batch Command -X"
   The -X command (External Flags)

   Syntax: PM -X{[h][q][c]}

   Sets some flags which were originally set in your configuration file.

   The possible parameters are :

    h    #HOLDMEM
    q    #QUIET
    c    #ARCHIVEMETHOD CRUNCH

   Examples:

   PM -Xq         Continue current session with #QUIT

   PM -Xh         Continue current session with #HOLDMEM

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdX

@NODE PM_Batch_CmdEO "Batch Commands Execute Order"
  Command Execution Order

   This  is  the order in which PM will execute multiple orders in one PM
   command line :

   -?     PM Help
   -#     System Info
   -UT    Turbolize
   -UQ    Quick Message Writer
   -UK    Kill Statistics
   -UR    Request File
   -US    Send File
   -UX    Autoreply Utility
   -UD    Dos Processor Utility
   -L     List Areas
   -P     Print
   -E     Export
   -A     Archive
   -B     Salvage Bad
   -D     Delete
   -R     Renum
   -I     Import
   -W     INTERACTIVE session
   -C     Script Command Processor

@ENDNODE PM_Batch_CmdEO

@NODE PMScript "POINT MANAGER - SCRIPT Commands"
@PREV "PMBatch"
@NEXT "PMArexx"
   The SCRIPT Commands

   As  mentioned before, PM can execute a number of commands if you enter
   the command @{"PM -C" LINK PM_Batch_CmdC}, followed by the name of a predefined Script file.

   This has been provided in order to make it easier for you to enjoy the
   advantages of PM, and to automate some extensively used features.

   The  advantage  of  using Script (Batch) files is that PM can maintain
   all the needed information in memory (especially so if you are able to
   use  @{"#HOLDMEM" LINK HoldMem}.   Furthermore  a lot of functions will act faster when
   executed like this.

   An  added bonus is that when you use the Script file, you can override
   PM's internal command order.

   Please  remember  to check if you have enough memory before attempting
   this.

   What  follows is a brief description of the @{"Script commands" LINK PMScrCmds} available.
   The  reason  for  the  brief description is that they perform the same
   function as the various parameters, which have already been described,
   so  if  you  need more information about a particular command, look in
   chapters @{"INTERACTIVE Session" LINK PMIntSes} and @{"BATCH Commands" LINK PMBatch}.

   All the Script commands must be preceeded by a '$' (Ie.  $LIST etc.).

@ENDNODE PMScript

@NODE PMScrCmds "Script Commands"

             Script Commands

   @{" ARCHIVE  " LINK PM_Script_Arc}   @{" IMPORT   " LINK PM_Script_Imp}
   @{" BROWSE   " LINK PM_Script_Browse}   @{" LIST     " LINK PM_Script_List}
   @{" CLOCK    " LINK PM_Script_Clk}   @{" LOGLEVEL " LINK PM_Script_LLev}
   @{" CONFIG   " LINK PM_Script_CFG}   @{" PRINT    " LINK PM_Script_Prt}
   @{" DELETE   " LINK PM_Script_Del}   @{" QUIET    " LINK PM_Script_Quiet}
   @{" DOS      " LINK PM_Script_Dos}   @{" QUIT     " LINK PM_Script_Quit}
   @{" EXEC     " LINK PM_Script_Exec}   @{" RENUM    " LINK PM_Script_Renum}
   @{" EXPORT   " LINK PM_Script_Exp}   @{" TIMER    " LINK PM_Script_Timer}
   @{" FREQUEST " LINK PM_Script_Freq}   @{" WINDOW   " LINK PM_Script_Window}
   @{" FSEND    " LINK PM_Script_FSend}   @{" WRITE    " LINK PM_Script_Write} 

@ENDNODE PMScrCmds

@NODE PM_Script_Arc "Script Command ARCHIVE"
   Script command ARCHIVE

   Syntax: ARCHIVE type [area]

   ARCHIVEs the message(s) from the specified area.



   ATTENTION: If  you  wish to ARCHIVE all the message that were DELETEd,
              you must remember to call ARCHIVE first, then DELETE.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Arc

@NODE PM_Script_Browse "Script Command BROWSE"
   Script command BROWSE

   Syntax: BROWSE area [news]

   Opens the MESSAGE screen and if you specify NEWS, it will let you read
   the unread messages.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Browse

@NODE PM_Script_Clk "Script Command CLOCK"
   Script command CLOCK

   Syntax: CLOCK HH:MM:SS

   Waits until the time you have specified.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Clk

@NODE PM_Script_CFG "Script Command CONFIG"
   Script command CONFIG

   Syntax: CONFIG file

   Uses  the  specified file as a new configuration file, instead of your
   normal PManager.CFG.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_CFG

@NODE PM_Script_Del "Script Command DELETE"
   Script command DELETE

   Syntax: DELETE {D/N} number [area]

   DELETE messages in the area defined, either by DATE or by NUMBER.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Del

@NODE PM_Script_Dos "Script Command DOS"
   Script command DOS

   Syntax: DOS command

   Executes an AmigaDOS command.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Dos

@NODE PM_Script_Exec "Script Command EXEC"
   Script command EXEC

   Syntax: EXEC scriptfile number

   EXECutes the scriptfile specified the number of times you specify.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Exec

@NODE PM_Script_Exp "Script Command EXPORT"
   Script command EXPORT

   Syntax: EXPORT [area]

   Performs an EXPORT of the specified area, or all areas, if no area was
   specified.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Exp

@NODE PM_Script_Freq "Script Command FREQUEST"
   Script command FREQUEST

   Syntax: FREQUEST

   Calls the File Request utility.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Freq

@NODE PM_Script_FSend "Script Command FSEND"
   Script command FSEND

   Syntax: FSEND

   Calls the File Send utility.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_FSend

@NODE PM_Script_Imp "Script Command IMPORT"
   Script command IMPORT

   Syntax: IMPORT

   Performs  a  (real) IMPORT.  It is NOT possible to perform a simulated
   IMPORT with the Script command.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Imp

@NODE PM_Script_List "Script Command LIST"
   Script command LIST

   Syntax: LIST [area]

   LISTs details of the specified area.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_List

@NODE PM_Script_LLev "Script Command LOGLEVEL"
   Script command LOGLEVEL

   Syntax: LOGLEVEL n

   Set log level to n (Minimum 0 and Maximum 5).

@ENDNODE PM_Script_LLev

@NODE PM_Script_Prt "Script Command PRINT"
   Script command PRINT

   Syntax: PRINT [area] [number]

   PRINTs  the  message  (or  all)  from  the  specified area (or all) to
   STDOUT.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Prt

@NODE PM_Script_Quiet "Script Command QUIET"
   Script command QUIET

   Syntax: QUIET

   Corresponds to the @{"#QUIET" LINK Quiet}.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Quiet

@NODE PM_Script_Quit "Script Command QUIT"
   Script command QUIT

   Syntax: QUIT

   Exit from the Script.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Quit

@NODE PM_Script_Renum "Script Command RENUM"
   Script command RENUM

   Syntax: RENUM {D/N} [area]

   Performs a RENUMber of the specified area.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Renum

@NODE PM_Script_Timer "Script Command TIMER"
   Script command TIMER

   Syntax: TIMER seconds

   Waits until the specified number of seconds have passed.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Timer

@NODE PM_Script_Window "Script Command WINDOW"
   Script command WINDOW

   Syntax: WINDOW

   Opens PM in @{"Interactive mode" LINK PMIntSes}.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Window

@NODE PM_Script_Write "Script Command WRITE"
   Script command WRITE

   Syntax: WRITE area

   Lets you write a message in the specified area.

@ENDNODE PM_Script_Write

@NODE PMArexx "AREXX Support"
@PREV "PMScript"
@NEXT "Conclusion"
@TOC "Operation"
   AREXX support

   Version 3.21 features limited AREXX support.

   The ARexx-port is named "PointManager".

   Commands available:

    @{" Archive     " LINK PM_Script_Arc}
    @{" Browse      " LINK PM_Script_Browse}
    @{" Delete      " LINK PM_Script_Del}
    @{" Export      " LINK PM_Script_Exp}
    @{" FreeAreaMem " LINK FreeAreaMem}
    @{" FRequest    " LINK PM_Script_Freq}
    @{" FSend       " LINK PM_Script_FSend}
    @{" Import      " LINK PM_Script_Imp}
    @{" Print       " LINK PM_Script_Prt}
    @{" Renum       " LINK PM_Script_Renum}
    @{" Write       " LINK PM_Script_Write}

   The Syntax are the same as in the related script command.

@ENDNODE PMArexx

@NODE FreeAreaMem "FreeAreaMem"
@TOC "PMArexx"
   FreeAreaMem

   This  gadget  will  Free  the memory allocated for the selected Areas.
   (This could be useful in memory panic situations).

   It will also update the Index files of the selected areas.

@ENDNODE FreeAreaMem

@NODE Conclusion "Conclusion of PM V3.21"
   Conclusion

   If  you  have any suggestions, questions or BUG reports, you can reach
   me or my support-team at this addresses:

              Pino Aliberti                 German Support
              2:335/602.2@fidonet           Siggi Weisner
              39:102/1.2@amiganet           2:243/4802.29@fidonet

   There  are also an international FidoNet Echomail conference called PM
   and  a  German  Echo called PM.GER, which should be available at major
   backbones.   This Areas should allow the users and the author of Point
   Manager to get closer together, to keep a closer contact.

   In  this  Areas,  you  can  freely exchange your experience with Point
   Manager, discuss future enhancements you would like to see etc.

   The  availability  of new versions of  Point Manager will be announced
   there, too.

   With  this version I've ulteriorly increased the steadiness of PM, now
   it should be 'steady as rock' *:^].

   I've also fixed all the known Enforcer hits.


   I  will  send  registered  users  a disk with the latest Point Manager
   version  together  with a keyfile and a @{"serial number" LINK Serial_Number}.  If you ask for
   it  in  your  registration  form,  I'll  send  you  a  special version
   optimized  for a 68030 processor.  This will increase PM's performance
   on 68030 based machines.

@ENDNODE Conclusion

@NODE Registration "Registration of PM V3.21"
   Registration

     Actually  it  is  possible to register your copy of Point Manager at
     one of these sites:


     Italy          - Pino Aliberti  2:335/602.2
     Germany        - Siggi Weisner  2:243/4802.29

     The method for registering at each of these sites is a little
     different, so please read the instructions for each very carefully.


